{"title_page": "Nick Thomas-Symonds", "text_new": "{{short description|Welsh Labour politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name             = Nick Thomas-Symonds\n|honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRHistS|size=100%}} [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n|image = Official portrait of Nick Thomas-Symonds crop 2.jpg\n|office1           =  [[Solicitor General for England and Wales|Shadow Solicitor General for England and Wales]]\n|leader1           = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start1       = 9 October 2016\n|predecessor1      = [[Jo Stevens]]\n|office2           = [[Home Office|Shadow Minister of State for Security]]\n|leader2           = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start2       = 5 July 2017\n|predecessor2      = ''Office established''\n|office3           = [[Department for Work and Pensions|Shadow Minister of State for Employment]]\n|leader3           = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start3      = 11 January 2016\n|term_end3         = 27 June 2016\n|predecessor3      = [[Emily Thornberry]]\n|successor3        = [[Margaret Greenwood]]\n|office4         = [[Department for Work and Pensions|Shadow Minister of State for Pensions]]\n|leader4          = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start4      = 17 September 2015\n|term_end4        = 11 January 2016 \n|predecessor4     = [[Gregg McClymont]]\n|successor4       =[[Angela Rayner]] \n|majority1        = \n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1980|5|26|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = {{Nowrap|[[Blaenavon]], Wales, United Kingdom}}\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|spouse           = Rebecca Nelson\n|alma_mater       = [[St Edmund Hall, Oxford]]\n|office5 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Torfaen (UK Parliament constituency)|Torfaen]]\n|predecessor5 = [[Paul Murphy, Baron Murphy of Torfaen|Paul Murphy]]\n|majority5 = 3,742 (10.0%)\n|term_start5 = 7 May 2015\n|term_end5=}}\n'''Nicklaus Thomas-Symonds''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|FRHistS|size=100%|sep=, }} (born 26 May 1980) is a [[Welsh People|Welsh]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician, [[barrister]], and academic serving as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Torfaen (UK Parliament constituency)|Torfaen]] since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/W07000053|title=Torfaen|work=bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Before entering Parliament, he was a [[Equity (law)|chancery]] and commercial [[barrister]] at Civitas Law.<ref>{{cite web | last = Simmons | first = Richard | title = City solicitors, a 22-year old UKIP law grad and a barrister standing for the Whigs: the legal profession's MP hopefuls | url = http://l2b.thelawyer.com/home/insight/city-solicitors-a-22-year-old-ukip-law-grad-and-a-barrister-standing-for-the-whigs-the-legal-professions-mp-hopefuls/3033862.article | website = Lawyer 2B | date = 10 April 2015 | accessdate = 14 September 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Profile: Nick Thomas-Symonds | url = http://www.civitaslaw.com/members/nick-thomas-symonds.aspx | website = Civitas Law | accessdate = 14 September 2015 }}</ref> He is also the author of ''Attlee: A Life in Politics'' and ''Nye: The Political Life of Aneurin Bevan.''\n\n==Early life and education==\nThomas-Symonds was born in Panteg Hospital, [[Griffithstown]], [[Torfaen]], and was brought up in [[Blaenavon]]. He attended St. Felix R.C. Primary School, Blaenavon, and [[St Alban's Roman Catholic High School, Pontypool|St. Alban's R.C. High School, Pontypool]]. He then studied [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics]] at [[St Edmund Hall, Oxford]], between 1998 and 2001.<ref name=\"bio - St Edmund Hall\" />\n\n==Career==\n\n===Legal career===\nThomas-Symonds was [[called to the bar]] by [[Lincoln's Inn]] in October 2004<ref name=\"bio - St Edmund Hall\">{{cite web|title=Nicklaus Thomas-Symonds|url=https://www.seh.ox.ac.uk/users/nicklausthomas-symonds|website=St Edmund Hall|publisher=University of Oxford|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref> and developed a practice specialising in chancery and commercial law.\n\n===Academic career===\nThomas-Symonds was appointed a Don at [[St Edmund Hall, Oxford|St. Edmund Hall, Oxford]], at the age of 21 and became Lecturer in Politics at the college, teaching British Politics and Government since 1900; Modern British Government and Politics; Government and Politics of Europe; and Government and Politics of the United States. He is the youngest individual to be appointed as an Oxford Don, since 1945. Thomas-Symonds taught for other Oxford colleges, including [[Harris Manchester College, Oxford|Harris Manchester College]]. He also taught US Politics on the Oxford Department of Continuing Education's \"Foundations of Diplomacy\" course.<ref name=\"ox\">{{cite web|url=http://www.seh.ox.ac.uk/users/nicklausthomas-symonds|publisher=seh.ox.ac.uk|title=Home &#124; St Edmund Hall|accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref>  He was elected a Fellow of the [[Royal Historical Society]] in 2012.\n\nThomas-Symonds has published two political biographies: ''Nye: The Political Life of Aneurin Bevan'' and ''Attlee: A Life in Politics.''\n\n===Political career===\nThomas-Symonds was selected as prospective Labour parliamentary candidate for Torfaen on 7 March 2015 and subsequently won the seat in the General Election on 7 May 2015. He made his maiden speech on 28 May 2015, without notes. [[Chris Bryant]] MP said he had delivered the speech \u201cwith panache\u201d.\n\nAfter a brief stint on the Justice Select Committee, he was appointed Shadow Pensions Minister on 17 September 2015 before being promoted to Shadow Employment Minister on 11 January 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://citywire.co.uk/new-model-adviser/news/labour-names-first-time-mp-as-shadow-pensions-minister/a843108|title=Labour names first-time MP as shadow pensions minister|work=Citywire|access-date=2017-07-10|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torfaenlabour.com/2016/01/13/nick-thomas-symonds-appointed-shadow-minister-for-employment/|title=Nick Thomas-Symonds appointed Shadow Minister for Employment|date=2016-01-13|website=Torfaen Constituency Labour Party|access-date=2017-07-10}}</ref> He resigned the role of Shadow Employment Minister on 27 June 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/gwentnews/14582404.Torfaen_MP_latest_to_quit_Labour_front_bench/|title=Torfaen MP latest to quit Labour front bench|website=South Wales Argus|language=en|access-date=2017-07-10}}</ref> later supporting [[Owen Smith]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/mps-nominating-owen-smith-labour-8451186|title=Which MPs are nominating Owen Smith in the Labour leadership contest?|last1=Smith|first1=Mikey|date=20 July 2016|work=Mirror|access-date=10 November 2018|last2=Bloom|first2=Dan|location=}}</ref> On 11 October 2016 he accepted the position of Shadow Solicitor General and on 3 July 2017 he was appointed as Shadow Security Minister within the Shadow Home Affairs Team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nickthomassymonds.uk/nick-thomas-symonds-promoted-to-shadow-solicitor-general/|title=Nick Thomas-Symonds promoted to Shadow Solicitor General \u2013 Nick Thomas Symonds MP|website=www.nickthomassymonds.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-07-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newsocialist.org.uk/reshuffle-2-the-ma/|title=Reshuffle 2: The Maintenance of the Malcontents|date=2017-07-08|work=New Socialist.|access-date=2017-07-10}}</ref>\n\nHe has served as Chair of four All-Party Parliamentary Groups: Off-Patent Drugs; Industrial Heritage; Legal & Constitutional Affairs; and Archives & History.<ref name=\"parliament1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/160428/industrial-heritage.htm|publisher=publications.parliament.uk|title=Register Of All-Party Parliamentary Groups [as at 28 April 2016]|accessdate=19 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nNick Thomas-Symonds was drawn in the ballot for a Private Members\u2019 Bill on 4 June 2015 and introduced the Off-Patent Drugs Bill. This ran out of time at Second Reading on 6 November 2015,<ref name=\"parliament2\">{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm151106/debtext/151106-0002.htm#15110644000858|publisher=publications.parliament.uk|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 06 Nov 2015 (pt 0002)|accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref> but substantial parts of the Bill were later incorporated into the Access to Medical Treatments (Innovation) Bill on 29 January 2016.<ref name=\"parliament3\">{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm160129/debtext/160129-0001.htm#16012937000706|publisher=publications.parliament.uk|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 29 Jan 2016 (pt 0001)|accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref> As a result of promises secured by Thomas-Symonds  the British National Formulary has started to include off-label drugs in their new indication where there is sufficient evidence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/15249908.torfaen-mps-bill-leads-to-british-national-formulary-review-of-prescription-drugs-bible/|title=MP's bill leads to review of drug 'Bible'|website=South Wales Argus|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 December 2015, Nick Thomas-Symonds was chosen as \u201cMember to Watch\u201d at the Welsh Politician of the Year Awards.<ref name=\"itv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/wales/2015-12-08/plaid-leader-named-welsh-politician-of-year/|publisher=itv.com|title=Plaid Cymru leader Leanne Wood named Welsh Politician of the Year &#124; Wales \u2013 ITV News|accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n* {{cite book|last1=Thomas-Symonds|first1=Nicklaus|title=Attlee: a life in politics|date=2010|publisher=I.B. Tauris|location=London|isbn=978-1845117795}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Thomas-Symonds|first1=Nicklaus|title=Nye: The Political Life of Aneurin Bevan|date=2014|publisher=I.B. Tauris|location=London|isbn=978-1780762098}}\n\n===Articles===\n* \u2018[https://journals.library.wales/view/1337678/1340775/4 The Battle of Grosmont, 1405: A Reinterpretation]\u2019 Gwent Local History, Volume 97, Autumn 2004. (Researched by Gareth McCann).\n* \u2018Michael Foot\u2019s Handling of the Militant Tendency: A Reinterpretation,\u2019 Contemporary British History, Volume 19, No 1, Spring 2005.\n* \u2018Oratory, Rhetoric and Politics: Neil Kinnock\u2019s Thousand Generations Speech of 1987,\u2019 Llafur: Journal of the Welsh People's History Society, Vol. 9, No. 3, 2006.\n* \u2018The Hard Sell: When does a new car actually belong to the purchaser?' Solicitors\u2019 Journal, Volume 154, Number 35, 21 September 2010.\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1093/pa/gss001|title=The Problem of the 'Lame Duck' Government: A Critique of the Fixed-term Parliaments Act|journal=Parliamentary Affairs|volume=66|issue=3|pages=540\u2013556|year=2013|last1=Youngs|first1=R.|last2=Thomas-Symonds|first2=N.}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=nick-thomas-symonds/4479 |publicwhip=Nick_Thomas-Symonds |theywork=nick_thomas-symonds}}\n*[http://cv.democracyclub.org.uk/show_cv/6689  Nick Thomas-Symonds CV at Democracy Club]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Paul Murphy, Baron Murphy of Torfaen|Paul Murphy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Torfaen (UK Parliament constituency)|Torfaen]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Wales Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas-Symonds, Nick}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Edmund Hall, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Welsh Labour Party MPs]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Historical Society]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Welsh Labour politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name             = Nick Thomas-Symonds\n|honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRHistS|size=100%}} [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n|image = Official portrait of Nick Thomas-Symonds crop 2.jpg\n|office1           =  [[Solicitor General for England and Wales|Shadow Solicitor General for England and Wales]]\n|leader1           = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start1       = 9 October 2016\n|predecessor1      = [[Jo Stevens]]\n|office2           = [[Home Office|Shadow Minister of State for Security]]\n|leader2           = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start2       = 5 July 2017\n|predecessor2      = ''Office established''\n|office3           = [[Department for Work and Pensions|Shadow Minister of State for Employment]]\n|leader3           = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start3      = 11 January 2016\n|term_end3         = 27 June 2016\n|predecessor3      = [[Emily Thornberry]]\n|successor3        = [[Margaret Greenwood]]\n|office4         = [[Department for Work and Pensions|Shadow Minister of State for Pensions]]\n|leader4          = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start4      = 17 September 2015\n|term_end4        = 11 January 2016 \n|predecessor4     = [[Gregg McClymont]]\n|successor4       =[[Angela Rayner]] \n|majority1        = \n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1980|5|26|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = {{Nowrap|[[Blaenavon]], Wales, United Kingdom}}\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|spouse           = Rebecca Nelson\n|alma_mater       = [[St Edmund Hall, Oxford]]\n|office5 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Torfaen (UK Parliament constituency)|Torfaen]]\n|predecessor5 = [[Paul Murphy, Baron Murphy of Torfaen|Paul Murphy]]\n|majority5 = 3,742 (10.0%)\n|term_start5 = 7 May 2015\n|term_end5=}}\n'''Nicklaus Thomas-Symonds''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|FRHistS|size=100%|sep=, }} (born 26 May 1980) is a [[Welsh People|Welsh]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician, [[barrister]], and academic serving as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Torfaen (UK Parliament constituency)|Torfaen]] since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/W07000053|title=Torfaen|work=bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Before entering Parliament, he was a [[Equity (law)|chancery]] and commercial [[barrister]] at Civitas Law.<ref>{{cite web | last = Simmons | first = Richard | title = City solicitors, a 22-year old UKIP law grad and a barrister standing for the Whigs: the legal profession's MP hopefuls | url = http://l2b.thelawyer.com/home/insight/city-solicitors-a-22-year-old-ukip-law-grad-and-a-barrister-standing-for-the-whigs-the-legal-professions-mp-hopefuls/3033862.article | website = Lawyer 2B | date = 10 April 2015 | accessdate = 14 September 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Profile: Nick Thomas-Symonds | url = http://www.civitaslaw.com/members/nick-thomas-symonds.aspx | website = Civitas Law | accessdate = 14 September 2015 }}</ref> He is also the author of ''Attlee: A Life in Politics'' and ''Nye: The Political Life of Aneurin Bevan.''\n\n==Early life and education==\nThomas-Symonds was born in Panteg Hospital, [[Griffithstown]], [[Torfaen]], and was brought up in [[Blaenavon]]. He attended St. Felix R.C. Primary School, Blaenavon, and [[St Alban's Roman Catholic High School, Pontypool|St. Alban's R.C. High School, Pontypool]]. He then studied [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics]] at [[St Edmund Hall, Oxford]], between 1998 and 2001.<ref name=\"bio - St Edmund Hall\" />\n\n==Career==\n\n===Legal career===\nThomas-Symonds was [[called to the bar]] by [[Lincoln's Inn]] in October 2004<ref name=\"bio - St Edmund Hall\">{{cite web|title=Nicklaus Thomas-Symonds|url=https://www.seh.ox.ac.uk/users/nicklausthomas-symonds|website=St Edmund Hall|publisher=University of Oxford|accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref> and developed a practice specialising in chancery and commercial law.\n\n===Academic career===\nThomas-Symonds was appointed a Don at [[St Edmund Hall, Oxford|St. Edmund Hall, Oxford]], at the age of 21 and became Lecturer in Politics at the college, teaching British Politics and Government since 1900; Modern British Government and Politics; Government and Politics of Europe; and Government and Politics of the United States. He is the youngest individual to be appointed as an Oxford Don, since 1945. Thomas-Symonds taught for other Oxford colleges, including [[Harris Manchester College, Oxford|Harris Manchester College]]. He also taught US Politics on the Oxford Department of Continuing Education's 'Foundations of Diplomacy' course.<ref name=\"ox\">{{cite web|url=http://www.seh.ox.ac.uk/users/nicklausthomas-symonds|publisher=seh.ox.ac.uk|title=Home &#124; St Edmund Hall|accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref>  He was elected a Fellow of the [[Royal Historical Society]] in 2012.\n\nThomas-Symonds has published two political biographies: ''Nye: The Political Life of Aneurin Bevan'' and ''Attlee: A Life in Politics.''\n\n===Political career===\nThomas-Symonds was selected as prospective Labour parliamentary candidate for Torfaen on 7 March 2015 and subsequently won the seat in the General Election on 7 May 2015. He made his maiden speech on 28 May 2015, without notes. [[Chris Bryant]] MP said he had delivered the speech \u201cwith panache\u201d.\n\nAfter a brief stint on the Justice Select Committee, he was appointed Shadow Pensions Minister on 17 September 2015 before being promoted to Shadow Employment Minister on 11 January 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://citywire.co.uk/new-model-adviser/news/labour-names-first-time-mp-as-shadow-pensions-minister/a843108|title=Labour names first-time MP as shadow pensions minister|work=Citywire|access-date=2017-07-10|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torfaenlabour.com/2016/01/13/nick-thomas-symonds-appointed-shadow-minister-for-employment/|title=Nick Thomas-Symonds appointed Shadow Minister for Employment|date=2016-01-13|website=Torfaen Constituency Labour Party|access-date=2017-07-10}}</ref> He resigned the role of Shadow Employment Minister on 27 June 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/gwentnews/14582404.Torfaen_MP_latest_to_quit_Labour_front_bench/|title=Torfaen MP latest to quit Labour front bench|website=South Wales Argus|language=en|access-date=2017-07-10}}</ref> later supporting [[Owen Smith]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/mps-nominating-owen-smith-labour-8451186|title=Which MPs are nominating Owen Smith in the Labour leadership contest?|last1=Smith|first1=Mikey|date=20 July 2016|work=Mirror|access-date=10 November 2018|last2=Bloom|first2=Dan|location=}}</ref> On 11 October 2016 he accepted the position of Shadow Solicitor General and on 3 July 2017 he was appointed as Shadow Security Minister within the Shadow Home Affairs Team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nickthomassymonds.uk/nick-thomas-symonds-promoted-to-shadow-solicitor-general/|title=Nick Thomas-Symonds promoted to Shadow Solicitor General \u2013 Nick Thomas Symonds MP|website=www.nickthomassymonds.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-07-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newsocialist.org.uk/reshuffle-2-the-ma/|title=Reshuffle 2: The Maintenance of the Malcontents|date=2017-07-08|work=New Socialist.|access-date=2017-07-10}}</ref>\n\nHe has served as Chair of four All-Party Parliamentary Groups: Off-Patent Drugs; Industrial Heritage; Legal & Constitutional Affairs; and Archives & History.<ref name=\"parliament1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/160428/industrial-heritage.htm|publisher=publications.parliament.uk|title=Register Of All-Party Parliamentary Groups [as at 28 April 2016]|accessdate=19 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nNick Thomas-Symonds was drawn in the ballot for a Private Members\u2019 Bill on 4 June 2015 and introduced the Off-Patent Drugs Bill. This ran out of time at Second Reading on 6 November 2015,<ref name=\"parliament2\">{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm151106/debtext/151106-0002.htm#15110644000858|publisher=publications.parliament.uk|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 06 Nov 2015 (pt 0002)|accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref> but substantial parts of the Bill were later incorporated into the Access to Medical Treatments (Innovation) Bill on 29 January 2016.<ref name=\"parliament3\">{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm160129/debtext/160129-0001.htm#16012937000706|publisher=publications.parliament.uk|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 29 Jan 2016 (pt 0001)|accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref> As a result of promises secured by Thomas-Symonds  the British National Formulary has started to include off-label drugs in their new indication where there is sufficient evidence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/15249908.torfaen-mps-bill-leads-to-british-national-formulary-review-of-prescription-drugs-bible/|title=MP's bill leads to review of drug 'Bible'|website=South Wales Argus|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 December 2015, Nick Thomas-Symonds was chosen as \u201cMember to Watch\u201d at the Welsh Politician of the Year Awards.<ref name=\"itv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/wales/2015-12-08/plaid-leader-named-welsh-politician-of-year/|publisher=itv.com|title=Plaid Cymru leader Leanne Wood named Welsh Politician of the Year &#124; Wales \u2013 ITV News|accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n* {{cite book|last1=Thomas-Symonds|first1=Nicklaus|title=Attlee: a life in politics|date=2010|publisher=I.B. Tauris|location=London|isbn=978-1845117795}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Thomas-Symonds|first1=Nicklaus|title=Nye: The Political Life of Aneurin Bevan|date=2014|publisher=I.B. Tauris|location=London|isbn=978-1780762098}}\n\n===Articles===\n* \u2018[https://journals.library.wales/view/1337678/1340775/4 The Battle of Grosmont, 1405: A Reinterpretation]\u2019 Gwent Local History, Volume 97, Autumn 2004. (Researched by Gareth McCann).\n* \u2018Michael Foot\u2019s Handling of the Militant Tendency: A Reinterpretation,\u2019 Contemporary British History, Volume 19, No 1, Spring 2005.\n* \u2018Oratory, Rhetoric and Politics: Neil Kinnock\u2019s Thousand Generations Speech of 1987,\u2019 Llafur: Journal of the Welsh People's History Society, Vol. 9, No. 3, 2006.\n* \u2018The Hard Sell: When does a new car actually belong to the purchaser?' Solicitors\u2019 Journal, Volume 154, Number 35, 21 September 2010.\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.1093/pa/gss001|title=The Problem of the 'Lame Duck' Government: A Critique of the Fixed-term Parliaments Act|journal=Parliamentary Affairs|volume=66|issue=3|pages=540\u2013556|year=2013|last1=Youngs|first1=R.|last2=Thomas-Symonds|first2=N.}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=nick-thomas-symonds/4479 |publicwhip=Nick_Thomas-Symonds |theywork=nick_thomas-symonds}}\n*[http://cv.democracyclub.org.uk/show_cv/6689  Nick Thomas-Symonds CV at Democracy Club]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Paul Murphy, Baron Murphy of Torfaen|Paul Murphy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Torfaen (UK Parliament constituency)|Torfaen]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Wales Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas-Symonds, Nick}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Edmund Hall, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Welsh Labour Party MPs]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u2013201