{"title_page": "Siege of Jerusalem", "text_new": "{{See also|Timeline of Jerusalem}}\n{{Jerusalem large}}\nThe '''Siege of Jerusalem''' may refer to several historical events, several of which (for instance 587 BC, AD 70, 637/38, 1187) are also called the '''Fall of Jerusalem'''. Some events listed here did not involve sieges for instance in 1917 and 1967.\n\n==Battles==\n*[[Siege of Jebus]] (1010 BC; event from biblical narrative) by [[David]], king of the [[Kingdom of Israel (united monarchy)|United Kingdom of Israel]], after which David converted the Canaanite city of Jebus into the Israelite capital called City of David, later Jerusalem.\n*[[Sack of Jerusalem (925 BC)]] (event from biblical narrative) by Pharaoh Shishaq, commonly identified as [[Shoshenq I]] of the [[Twenty-second Dynasty of Egypt|Twenty-second Dynasty]].\n*[[Assyrian Siege of Jerusalem]] (701 BC) by [[Sennacherib]], king of the [[Neo-Assyrian Empire]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (597 BC)]] by [[Nebuchadnezzar II]] of the [[Neo-Babylonian Empire]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (587 BC)]] and destruction of the city and the [[First Temple]] by [[Nebuchadnezzar II]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (134 BC)]] by [[Antiochus VII Sidetes]] of the [[Seleucid Empire]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (67 BC)]] by King [[Aristobulus II]] of Judea against his brother King [[Hyrcanus II]], beginning the [[Hasmonean Civil War]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (64 BC)]] by [[Hyrcanus II]] of Judea and allied [[Nabateans]] against [[Aristobulus II]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (63 BC)]] by [[Pompey the Great]], intervening in the Hasmonean civil war. Judaea falls under the rule of [[Ancient Rome]] for the next seven centuries.\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (63 BC)]] by [[Pompey the Great]], bringing about the incorporation of Judea into the [[Roman Republic]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (37 BC)]] by [[Herod the Great]], ending [[Hasmonean]] rule over Judea.\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (AD 70)]] by [[Titus]], ending the major phase of the [[Great Jewish Revolt]]. It ended in the destruction of the city including [[Herod's Temple]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (614)]] by [[Shahrbaraz]], lead to the [[Sasanian Empire|Sassanid]] general capturing the city from the Byzantines; part of the Roman-Persian Wars.\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (636\u2013637)|Siege of Jerusalem (636\u2013637 or 638)]] by [[Khalid ibn al-Walid]] (Rashidun general) under [[Umar ibn al-Khattab]], ending in the surrender of the  [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] city.\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (1099)]] by the Crusaders, resulting in the capture of the city, the goal of the [[First Crusade]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (1187)]] by [[Saladin]], resulting in the capture of the city by the Muslims.\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (1244)]] by the [[Khwarazmian dynasty|Khwarezmians]], resulting in the recapture of the city from the Christians, to whom it had been returned by treaty.\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (1834)]] by Arab villagers during the [[1834 Arab revolt in Palestine]].\n*[[Battle of Jerusalem]] (1917) involved the capture of the city in the Sinai and Palestine campaign of World War I by British and Commonwealth forces.\n*[[Battle for Jerusalem (1948)]] during the 1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War. The city was divided between Jordan and Israel; Israel made Jerusalem its capital.\n*An [[Six-Day War#West Bank|encirclement of East Jerusalem]] occurred in 1967, which was completed with the [[Battle of Ammunition Hill]]; however, the [[Six-Day War]] was short and decisive enough that a \"siege\" never quite took place.\n\n==In literature==\n* ''[[The Siege of Jerusalem]]'', 1771 poetical drama by [[Mary Bowes, Countess of Strathmore and Kinghorne]] also depicting events of AD 70.\n* ''[[Siege of Jerusalem (poem)]]'', 14th-century Middle English alliterative poem depicting the events of AD 70.\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n[[Category:Sieges of Jerusalem]]\n[[Category:Military history of Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{See also|Timeline of Jerusalem}}\n{{Jerusalem large}}\nThe '''Siege of Jerusalem''' may refer to several historical events, several of which (for instance 587 BC, AD 70, 637/38, 1187) are also called the '''Fall of Jerusalem'''. Some events listed here did not involve sieges for instance in 1917 and 1967.\n\n==Battles==\n*[[Siege of Jebus]] (1010 BC; event from biblical narrative) by [[David]], biblical king of the [[Kingdom of Israel (united monarchy)|United Kingdom of Israel]], after which David converted the Canaanite city of Jebus into the Israelite capital called City of David, later Jerusalem.\n*[[Sack of Jerusalem (925 BC)]] (event from biblical narrative) by Pharaoh Shishaq, commonly identified as [[Shoshenq I]] of the [[Twenty-second Dynasty of Egypt|Twenty-second Dynasty]].\n*[[Assyrian Siege of Jerusalem]] (701 BC) by [[Sennacherib]], king of the [[Neo-Assyrian Empire]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (597 BC)]] by [[Nebuchadnezzar II]] of the [[Neo-Babylonian Empire]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (587 BC)]] and destruction of the city and the [[First Temple]] by [[Nebuchadnezzar II]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (134 BC)]] by [[Antiochus VII Sidetes]] of the [[Seleucid Empire]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (67 BC)]] by King [[Aristobulus II]] of Judea against his brother King [[Hyrcanus II]], beginning the [[Hasmonean Civil War]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (64 BC)]] by [[Hyrcanus II]] of Judea and allied [[Nabateans]] against [[Aristobulus II]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (63 BC)]] by [[Pompey the Great]], intervening in the Hasmonean civil war. Judaea falls under the rule of [[Ancient Rome]] for the next seven centuries.\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (63 BC)]] by [[Pompey the Great]], bringing about the incorporation of Judea into the [[Roman Republic]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (37 BC)]] by [[Herod the Great]], ending [[Hasmonean]] rule over Judea.\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (AD 70)]] by [[Titus]], ending the major phase of the [[Great Jewish Revolt]]. It ended in the destruction of the city including [[Herod's Temple]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (614)]] by [[Shahrbaraz]], lead to the [[Sasanian Empire|Sassanid]] general capturing the city from the Byzantines; part of the Roman-Persian Wars.\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (636\u2013637)|Siege of Jerusalem (636\u2013637 or 638)]] by [[Khalid ibn al-Walid]] (Rashidun general) under [[Umar ibn al-Khattab]], ending in the surrender of the  [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] city.\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (1099)]] by the Crusaders, resulting in the capture of the city, the goal of the [[First Crusade]].\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (1187)]] by [[Saladin]], resulting in the capture of the city by the Muslims.\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (1244)]] by the [[Khwarazmian dynasty|Khwarezmians]], resulting in the recapture of the city from the Christians, to whom it had been returned by treaty.\n*[[Siege of Jerusalem (1834)]] by Arab villagers during the [[1834 Arab revolt in Palestine]].\n*[[Battle of Jerusalem]] (1917) involved the capture of the city in the Sinai and Palestine campaign of World War I by British and Commonwealth forces.\n*[[Battle for Jerusalem (1948)]] during the 1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War. The city was divided between Jordan and Israel; Israel made Jerusalem its capital.\n*An [[Six-Day War#West Bank|encirclement of East Jerusalem]] occurred in 1967, which was completed with the [[Battle of Ammunition Hill]]; however, the [[Six-Day War]] was short and decisive enough that a \"siege\" never quite took place.\n\n==In literature==\n* ''[[The Siege of Jerusalem]]'', 1771 poetical drama by [[Mary Bowes, Countess of Strathmore and Kinghorne]] also depicting events of AD 70.\n* ''[[Siege of Jerusalem (poem)]]'', 14th-century Middle English alliterative poem depicting the events of AD 70.\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n[[Category:Sieges of Jerusalem]]\n[[Category:Military history of Asia]]\n", "name_user": "Arminden", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siege_of_Jerusalem"}
{"title_page": "La casa chica", "text_new": "{{short description|1948 film by Roberto Gavald\u00f3n}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name =  La casa chica\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| caption =\n| director = [[Roberto Gavald\u00f3n]]\n| producer =  Gregorio Walerstein\n| writer =   [[Jos\u00e9 Revueltas]] <br> Roberto Gavald\u00f3n\n| narrator =\n| starring = [[Dolores del R\u00edo]] <br> [[Roberto Ca\u00f1edo]] <br> [[Miroslava (actress)|Miroslava]]\n| music = Antonio D\u00edaz Conde\n| cinematography = [[Alex Phillips (cinematographer)|Alex Phillips]]\n| editing =  Rafael Ceballos\n| studio =  FILMEX\n| distributor =   \n| released = 9 February 1950\n| runtime = 115 minutes\n| country =  Mexico\n| language = [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n| budget =\n| gross =\n| preceded_by =\n| followed_by =\n| website =\n}}\n'''''La casa chica''''' (English: '''''The Little House''''') is a 1950 [[Mexico|Mexican]] [[drama film]] directed by [[Roberto Gavald\u00f3n]] and starring [[Dolores del R\u00edo]].\n\n==Plot==\nFernando Mendoza, an eminent doctor, falls in love with Amalia, a sweet woman that fully reciprocates. But Fernando is engaged to marry Lucila, a frivolous woman who uses a thousand wiles to keep him.\n\nOver the years, the stormy relationship between Fernando and Amalia becomes more complicated. She finishes her medical studies and becomes a very prestigious scientist. Amalia agrees to become Fernando's lover and collaborates with him in his laboratory as his \"assistant\". They share an apartment, \"the house of the other\", where they enjoy their pure and sincere love.<ref>[http://www.correcamara.com.mx/inicio/int.php?mod=columnas_detalle&id_columna=1370 ''CorreCamara.com: Mexican melodramas \"La casa chica\"'']</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Dolores del R\u00edo]] as Amalia Estrada\n* [[Roberto Ca\u00f1edo]] as Dr. Fernando Mendoza\n* [[Miroslava (actress)|Miroslava]] as Lucila del Castillo\n* [[Domingo Soler]] as Professor Alfaro\n* [[Mar\u00eda Douglas]] as Nelly Guti\u00e9rrez\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0041230}}\n* [http://www.filmaffinity.com/mx/film834611.html ''La casa chica on FilmAffinity.com'']\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:casa chica}}\n[[Category:1950 films]]\n[[Category:1950s drama films]]\n[[Category:Mexican drama films]]\n[[Category:Mexican films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Roberto Gavald\u00f3n]]\n\n{{1950s-Mexico-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1948 film by Roberto Gavald\u00f3n}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name =  La casa chica\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| caption =\n| director = [[Roberto Gavald\u00f3n]]\n| producer =  Gregorio Walerstein\n| writer =   [[Jos\u00e9 Revueltas]] <br> Roberto Gavald\u00f3n\n| narrator =\n| starring = [[Dolores del R\u00edo]] <br> [[Roberto Ca\u00f1edo]] <br> [[Miroslava (actress)|Miroslava]]\n| music = Antonio D\u00edaz Conde\n| cinematography = [[Alex Phillips (cinematographer)|Alex Phillips]]\n| editing =  Rafael Ceballos\n| studio =  FILMEX\n| distributor =   \n| released = 9 February 1950\n| runtime = 115 minutes\n| country =  Mexico\n| language = [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n| budget =\n| gross =\n| preceded_by =\n| followed_by =\n| website =\n}}\n'''''La casa chica''''' (English: '''''The Little House''''') is a 1950 [[Mexico|Mexican]] [[drama film]] directed by [[Roberto Gavald\u00f3n]] and starring [[Dolores del R\u00edo]].\n\n==Plot==\nFernando Mendoza (Roberto Ca\u00f1edo), an eminent doctor, falls in love with Amalia (Dolores del R\u00edo), a sweet woman that fully reciprocates. But Fernando is engaged to marry Lucila (Miroslava), a frivolous woman who uses a thousand wiles to keep him.\n\nOver the years, the stormy relationship between Fernando and Amalia becomes more complicated. She finishes her medical studies and becomes a very prestigious scientist. Amalia agrees to become Fernando's lover and collaborates with him in his laboratory as his \"assistant\". They share an apartment, \"the house of the other\", where they enjoy their pure and sincere love.<ref>[http://www.correcamara.com.mx/inicio/int.php?mod=columnas_detalle&id_columna=1370 ''CorreCamara.com: Mexican melodramas \"La casa chica\"'']</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Dolores del R\u00edo]] as Amalia Estrada\n* [[Roberto Ca\u00f1edo]] as Dr. Fernando Mendoza\n* [[Miroslava (actress)|Miroslava]] as Lucila del Castillo\n* [[Domingo Soler]] as Professor Alfaro\n* [[Mar\u00eda Douglas]] as Nelly Guti\u00e9rrez\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0041230}}\n* [http://www.filmaffinity.com/mx/film834611.html ''La casa chica on FilmAffinity.com'']\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:casa chica}}\n[[Category:1950 films]]\n[[Category:1950s drama films]]\n[[Category:Mexican drama films]]\n[[Category:Mexican films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Roberto Gavald\u00f3n]]\n\n{{1950s-Mexico-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jmg38", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:Plot in \"Plot\", cast in \"Cast\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_casa_chica"}
{"title_page": "Marilynne Robinson", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Marilynne Robinson\n| image = Mariliynne Robinson.jpg\n| caption = Robinson at the 2012 Festival of Faith and Writing at [[Calvin College]]\n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = Marilynne Summers\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1943|11|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Sandpoint, Idaho]], US\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = {{hlist | Novelist | essayist}}\n| alma_mater = {{unbulleted list | [[Pembroke College in Brown University|Pembroke College, Brown]] | [[University of Washington]]}}\n| residence = [[Iowa City, Iowa]], US\n| period = \n| genre = \n| subject = \n| movement = \n| notableworks = {{unbulleted list | ''[[Housekeeping (novel)|Housekeeping]]'' (1980) | ''[[Gilead (novel)|Gilead]]'' (2004) | ''[[Home (Robinson novel)|Home]]'' (2008) | ''[[Lila (Robinson novel)|Lila]]'' (2014)}}\n| spouse = {{marriage|Fred Miller Robinson|1967|1989|reason=div}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MKm8CgAAQBAJ&pg=PR11&lpg=PR11&dq=marilynne+robinson+husband+divorce#v=onepage&q=marilynne%20robinson%20husband%20divorce&f=true|title=This Life, This World: New Essays on Marilynne Robinson's Housekeeping, Gilead, and Home|date=2015-09-25|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9789004302235|language=en}}</ref>\n| partner = \n| children = 2\n| relatives = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = {{unbulleted list | {{nowrap|[[Hemingway Foundation/PEN Award]]}} (1981) | [[National Book Critics Circle Award#Fiction|National Book Critics Circle Award for Fiction]] (2004, 2014) | [[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction]] (2005) | [[Orange Prize for Fiction]] (2009) | {{nowrap|[[National Humanities Medal]] (2012)}} | [[Library of Congress Prize for American Fiction]] (2016)}}\n| signature = \n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Marilynne Summers Robinson''' (born November 26, 1943) is an American novelist and essayist. Across her writing career, Robinson has received numerous awards, including the [[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction]] in 2005, [[National Humanities Medal]] in 2012, and the 2016 [[Library of Congress Prize for American Fiction]]. In 2016, Robinson was named in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's list of 100 most influential people.<ref>[http://time.com/4298233/marilynne-robinson-2016-time-100/ 100 Most Influential People Marilynne Robinson] ''Time'', April 2016</ref> Robinson began teaching at the [[Iowa Writers' Workshop]] in 1991<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news-releases.uiowa.edu/1998/february/0204robinson.html |title=UI Writers' Workshop faculty member Marilynne Robinson win quarter-million-dollar award |date=February 4, 1998 |accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref> and retired in the spring of 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://now.uiowa.edu/2016/04/robinson-retire-iowa-writers-workshop|title=Robinson to retire from Iowa Writers' Workshop|date=2016-04-27|website=Iowa Now|access-date=2016-04-27}}</ref>\n\nRobinson is best known for her novels ''[[Housekeeping (novel)|Housekeeping]]'' (1980) and ''[[Gilead (novel)|Gilead]]'' (2004). Her novels are noted for their thematic depiction of both rural life and faith.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/apr/03/fiction.features2 | title=A love letter to lost America |date=April 2, 2005 |accessdate=March 29, 2016| newspaper=The Guardian | last1=McCrum | first1=Robert }}</ref> The subjects of her essays have spanned numerous topics, including the [[relationship between religion and science]], [[History of the United States|US history]], [[Sellafield|nuclear pollution]], [[John Calvin]], and contemporary American politics.\n\n==Life and career==\nRobinson was born on November 26, 1943 in [[Sandpoint, Idaho]], the daughter of Eileen (Harris) and John J. Summers, a lumber company employee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arts.gov/art-works/2010/marilynne-robinson-sandpoint-memories|title=Marilynne Robinson: Sandpoint Memories|date=2010-04-06|website=NEA|language=en|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=U59bAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT3279&dq=%22toJohn+J.Summers,+a+lumbercompany+employee,+and+Ellen+Harris+Summers%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwil59Kuz9jjAhWTHM0KHT9HAf0Q6AEwAHoECAAQAQ]</ref><ref>https://www.hillandwood.com/obituary/1887647</ref> Her brother is the art historian [[David Summers (art historian)|David Summers]], who dedicated his book ''Vision, Reflection, and Desire in Western Painting'' to her. She did her undergraduate work at [[Pembroke College (Brown University)|Pembroke College]], the former [[women's college]] at [[Brown University]], receiving her [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree ''[[magna cum laude]]'' in 1966, where she was elected to [[Phi Beta Kappa]]. At Brown, one of her teachers was the celebrated postmodern novelist [[John Hawkes (novelist)|John Hawkes]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MKm8CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA19&lpg=PA19&dq=marilynne+robinson+lewis+tappan#v=onepage&q=brown%20university&f=false|title=This Life, This World: New Essays on Marilynne Robinson's Housekeeping, Gilead, and Home|date=2015-09-25|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9789004302235|language=en}}</ref> She received her [[Doctor of Philosophy]] degree in English from the [[University of Washington]] in 1977.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.washington.edu/uwired/outreach/cspn/Website/Classroom%20Materials/Reading%20the%20Region/Northwest%20Schools%20of%20Literature/Commentary/9.html|date= n.d.|accessdate= 2008-04-13| title=  \t\n''History & Literature of the Pacific Northwest: Marilynne Robinson, 1943''|work= Center for the Study of the Pacific Northwest, [[University of Washington]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.litencyc.com/php/speople.php?rec=true&UID=5955 |title=Marilynne Robinson (1947\u2013 ) |accessdate=2009-06-22 |last=Lister |first=Rachel |date=2006-10-21 |publisher=[[The Literary Encyclopedia]] }}</ref>\n\nRobinson has written four highly acclaimed novels: ''[[Housekeeping (novel)|Housekeeping]]'' (1980), ''[[Gilead (novel)|Gilead]]'' (2004), ''[[Home (Robinson novel)|Home]]'' (2008), and ''[[Lila (Robinson novel)|Lila]]'' (2014). ''Housekeeping'' was a finalist for the 1982 [[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction]] (US), ''Gilead'' was awarded the 2005 Pulitzer, and ''Home'' received the 2009 [[Orange Prize for Fiction]] (UK). ''Home'' and ''Lila are'' companions to ''Gilead'' and focus on the Boughton and Ames families during the same time period.<ref name=PW>{{cite web|url= http://us.macmillan.com/home|title= ''Home'' by Marilynne Robinson|publisher= Us.macmillan.com|accessdate= 2015-10-29|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100722063909/http://us.macmillan.com/home|archive-date= 2010-07-22|url-status= dead}}</ref><ref>Dave Itzkoff, [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/04/books/04arts-MARILYNNEROB_BRF.html \"Marilynne Robinson Wins Orange Prize\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', June 3, 2009.</ref>\n\nRobinson is also the author of many non-fiction works, including ''[[Mother Country: Britain, the Welfare State, and Nuclear Pollution]]'' (1989), ''The Death of Adam: Essays on Modern Thought'' (1998), ''Absence of Mind: The Dispelling of Inwardness from the Modern Myth of the Self'' (2010), ''When I Was a Child I Read Books: Essays'' (2012), ''The Givenness of Things: Essays'' (2015), and ''What Are We Doing Here?'' (2018). She has written numerous articles, essays and reviews for ''[[Harper's Magazine|Harper's]]'', ''[[The Paris Review]],'' and ''[[The New York Review of Books]].''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://harpers.org/archive/2016/03/save-our-public-universities/|title=Save Our Public Universities|last=Robinson|first=Marilynne|date=2016-03-01|newspaper=Harper's Magazine|access-date=2017-02-05|issn=0017-789X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theparisreview.org/interviews/5863/marilynne-robinson-the-art-of-fiction-no-198-marilynne-robinson|title=Marilynne Robinson, The Art of Fiction No. 198|last=Fay|first=Interviewed by Sarah|newspaper=The Paris Review|access-date=2017-02-05|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nybooks.com/contributors/marilynne-robinson/|title=Marilynne Robinson|website=The New York Review of Books|access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref>\n\nShe has been writer-in-residence or visiting professor at many universities, including the [[University of Kent]], [[Amherst College|Amherst]] (where she taught, among other illustrious students, the novelist [[David Foster Wallace]]), and the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]]'s [[MFA Program for Poets & Writers|MFA Program for Poets and Writers]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/d-f-w-week-the-wonderfully-arrogant-first-pitch-letter|title=D.F.W. Week: The Wonderfully Arrogant First Pitch Letter|last=Max|first=D. T.|date=2012-09-07|access-date=2019-04-02|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref> In 2009, she held a Dwight H. Terry Lectureship at [[Yale University]], where she delivered a series of talks titled ''Absence of Mind: The Dispelling of Inwardness from the Modern Myth of the Self''. On April 19, 2010, she was elected a fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amacad.org/news/pressReleaseContent.aspx?i=113 |title=American Academy of Arts & Sciences |publisher=Amacad.org |date= |accessdate=2015-10-29}}</ref> In May 2011, Robinson delivered the [[University of Oxford]]'s annual Esmond Harmsworth Lecture in American Arts and Letters at the university's [[Rothermere American Institute]].\n\nIn the Spring of 2016, she retired as the F. Wendell Miller Professor of English and Creative Writing at the [[Iowa Writers' Workshop]]. Robinson still lives in [[Iowa City]], and spends the summers with family in upstate New York.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/jul/06/marilynne-robinson-interview-barack-obama-donald-trump-writer-theologian|title=Marilynne Robinson: \u2018Obama was very gentlemanly ... I'd like to get a look at Trump\u2019|last=Allardice|first=Lisa|date=2018-07-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-04-02|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> She was the keynote speaker for the Workshop's 75th anniversary celebration in June 2011. She gave the 2012 Annual Buechner Lecture at [[Frederick Buechner#The Buechner Institute at King University|The Buechner Institute]] at [[King University]]. In 2012, Brown University awarded Robinson the degree of Doctor of Literature ''honoris causa''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=MKm8CgAAQBAJ&pg=PR16&lpg=PR16&dq=awarded+marilynne+Robinson+the+degree+of+Doctor+of+Literature+honoris+causa&source=bl&ots=cu6rlSPU9J&sig=ACfU3U3eaqh3A5l1MVr6yQlARSvPn6cXVw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjxm7Grt7DhAhVVWysKHUe_AsAQ6AEwAnoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=awarded%20marilynne%20Robinson%20the%20degree%20of%20Doctor%20of%20Literature%20honoris%20causa&f=false|title=This Life, This World: New Essays on Marilynne Robinson\u2019s Housekeeping, Gilead, and Home|date=2015-09-25|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9789004302235|language=en}}</ref> On February 18, 2013, she was the speaker at the Easter Convocation of the University of the South, Sewanee, Tennessee and was awarded the degree of Doctor of Literature ''honoris causa''. The College of the Holy Cross, Notre Dame, Amherst College, Skidmore College, the University of Oxford, and Yale University have also awarded Robinson honorary degrees. She has been elected a fellow of [[Mansfield College, Oxford]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mansfield.ox.ac.uk/news/marilynne-robinson-awarded-honorary-fellowship|title=Marilynne Robinson awarded Honorary Fellowship {{!}} Mansfield College, Oxford|website=www.mansfield.ox.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-01-18}}</ref>\n\nRobinson was raised as a [[Presbyterian]] and later became a [[Congregational church|Congregationalist]], worshipping and sometimes preaching at the [[Congregational United Church of Christ (Iowa City, Iowa)|Congregational United Church of Christ]] in Iowa City.<ref name=\"Reform\">[http://www.reform-magazine.co.uk/index.php/2010/08/marilynne-robinson-interview-the-faith-behind-the-fiction/ \"Marilynne Robinson interview: The faith behind the fiction\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201235102/http://www.reform-magazine.co.uk/index.php/2010/08/marilynne-robinson-interview-the-faith-behind-the-fiction/ |date=2011-02-01 }}, ''[[Reform (magazine)|Reform]]'', September 2010.</ref><ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wnet/religionandethics/episodes/september-18-2009/marilynne-robinson/4244/ \"Marilynne Robinson\"], ''[[Religion & Ethics Newsweekly]]'', September 18, 2009.</ref> Her Congregationalism and her interest in the ideas of [[John Calvin]] have been important in many of her novels, including ''Gilead'', which centers on the life and theological concerns of a fictional Congregationalist minister.<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wnet/religionandethics/week829/interview.html \"Marilynne Robinson\"], ''[[Religion & Ethics Newsweekly]]'', March 18, 2005.</ref> In an interview with the ''[[Church Times]]'' in 2012, Robinson said: \"I think, if people actually read Calvin, rather than read [[Max Weber]], he would be rebranded. He is a very respectable thinker.\"<ref>Wroe, Martin, \"[http://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2012/22-june/features/a-minister-of-the-word A minister of the word]\", ''Church Times'', 22 June 2012</ref>\n\nThe former Archbishop of Canterbury, [[Rowan Williams]], has described Robinson as \"one of the world's most compelling English-speaking novelists\", adding that \"Robinson's is a voice we urgently need to attend to in both Church and society here [in the UK].\"<ref>Williams, Rowan, \"[http://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2012/10-august/reviews/book-reviews/mighty-plea-for-reasonableness Mighty plea for reasonableness]\", ''Church Times'', 12 August 2012</ref> On January 24, 2013, Robinson was announced to be among the finalists for the 2013 [[Man Booker International Prize]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.themanbookerprize.com/news/man-booker-international-prize-2013-finalists-announced |title=Man Booker International Prize 2013 Finalists Announced &#124; The Man Booker Prizes |publisher=Themanbookerprize.com |date=2013-01-24 |accessdate=2015-10-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924192855/http://themanbookerprize.com/news/man-booker-international-prize-2013-finalists-announced |archivedate=2015-09-24 }}</ref>\n\nOn June 26, 2015, President [[Barack Obama]] quoted Robinson in his eulogy for [[Clementa C. Pinckney]] of [[Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church]] in Charleston, South Carolina. In speaking about \"an open heart,\" Obama said: \"[w]hat a friend of mine, the writer Marilynne Robinson, calls 'that reservoir of goodness, beyond, and of another kind, that we are able to do each other in the ordinary cause of things.'\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2015/06/26/remarks-president-eulogy-honorable-reverend-clementa-pinckney |title=Remarks by the President in Eulogy for the Honorable Reverend Clementa Pinckney |publisher=whitehouse.gov |date=2015-06-26 |accessdate=2015-10-29}}</ref> In November 2015, ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'' published a two-part conversation between Obama and Robinson, covering topics in American history and the role of faith in society.<ref>{{cite journal\n| url = http://www.nybooks.com/articles/2015/11/05/president-obama-marilynne-robinson-conversation/| title = President Obama & Marilynne Robinson: A Conversation in Iowa| journal = The New York Review of Books| date = November 5, 2015| accessdate = August 21, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n| url = http://www2.nybooks.com/articles/s3/2015/nov/19/president-obama-marilynne-robinson-conversation-2.html| title = President Obama & Marilynne Robinson: A Conversation\u2014II| journal = The New York Review of Books| date = November 19, 2015| accessdate = August 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Personal life===\nIn 1967 she married Fred Miller Robinson,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sandiego.edu/cas/film/faculty-and-staff/biography.php?profile_id=74|title=Biography - Fred Miller Robinson, PhD - College of Arts and Sciences - University of San Diego|website=www.sandiego.edu|access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sheerhubris.com/tag/marilynne-robinson/|title=Marilynne Robinson|last=Sandra Hutchison|website=Sandra Hutchison|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref> a writer and professor at the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]]. The Robinsons divorced in 1989.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theparisreview.org/interviews/5863/marilynne-robinson-the-art-of-fiction-no-198-marilynne-robinson|title=Marilynne Robinson, The Art of Fiction No. 198|last=Fay|first=Interviewed by Sarah|date=2008|work=The Paris Review|access-date=2019-01-03|issue=186|volume=Fall 2008|language=en|issn=0031-2037}}</ref> \n\nThe couple had two sons, James and Joseph. In the late 1970s, she wrote ''Housekeeping'' in the evenings while they slept. Robinson said they influenced her writing in many ways, since \"[Motherhood] changes your sense of life, your sense of yourself.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2009/may/30/marilynne-robinson|title=A life in writing: Marilynne Robinson|last=Brockes|first=Emma|date=2009-05-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-01-04|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Expand list|date=February 2015}}\n\n===Fiction===\n* ''[[Housekeeping (novel)|Housekeeping]]'' (1980) {{ISBN|9780374525187}}, {{OCLC|930404329}}\n* ''[[Gilead (novel)|Gilead]]'' (2004) {{ISBN|9780312424404}}, {{OCLC|1016128137}}\n* ''[[Home (Robinson novel)|Home]]'' (2008) {{ISBN|9780009732997}}, {{OCLC|588596243}}\n* ''[[Lila (Robinson novel)|Lila]]'' (2014) {{ISBN|9781844088812}}, {{OCLC|891809441}}<ref>[https://www.economist.com/blogs/theworldin2014/2013/11/cultural-forecasts \"Five books for 2014\"], ''The Economist'' November 21, 2013</ref>\n* ''Jack'' (2020)\n\n===Nonfiction===\n\n====Books====\n* ''[[Mother Country: Britain, the Welfare State, and Nuclear Pollution]]'' (1989) {{ISBN|9780374526597}}, {{OCLC|690002450}}\n* ''The Death of Adam: Essays on Modern Thought'' (1998) {{ISBN|9780312425326}}, {{OCLC|611655337}}\n* ''Absence of Mind: The Dispelling of Inwardness from the Modern Myth of the Self'' (2010) {{ISBN|9780300171471}}, {{OCLC|742007978}}\n* ''When I Was a Child I Read Books'' (2012)\n* ''The Givenness of Things: Essays'' (2015) {{ISBN|9781250097316}}, {{OCLC|930009863}}\n* ''What Are We Doing Here?: Essays'' (2018) {{ISBN|9780374282219}}, {{OCLC|988060584}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.92y.org/event/marilynne-robinson|title=Marilynne Robinson Introduced by Paul Elie|website=92 St Y}}</ref>\n\n====Essays and reporting====\n* {{cite journal |date=Winter 2011 |title=On \"beauty\" |journal=[[Tin House]] |volume=50}}\n* {{cite journal |date=November 2015 |title=Humanism, Science, and the Radical Expansion of the Possible |journal=[[The Nation]]|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/humanism-science-and-the-radical-expansion-of-the-possible/}}\n* {{cite journal |date=Fall 2015 |title=Fear |journal=[[New York Review of Books]] |volume=62 |number=14 |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/2015/09/24/marilynne-robinson-fear/}}\n* {{cite journal |date=Summer 2019 |title=Which Way to the City on a Hill?|journal=[[New York Review of Books]] |volume=66 |number=12 |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/2019/07/18/which-way-city-hill/}}\n\n====Interviews====\n* A September 2015 interview with [[Barack Obama]] in [[Des Moines]], [[Iowa]], recorded by the [[New York Review of Books]] and published in the October issues of the magazine in two-parts\n\n==Awards==\n* 1982: [[Hemingway Foundation/PEN Award]] for best first novel for ''[[Housekeeping (novel)|Housekeeping]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=PEN/Hemingway Award Winners|url=http://hemingwaysociety.org/?page_id=751|website=The Hemingway Society|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n* 1982: [[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction]] shortlist for ''[[Housekeeping (novel)|Housekeeping]]'' <ref>{{cite web|title=1982 Finalists|url=http://www.pulitzer.org/finalists/1982|website=The Pulitzer Prizes|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n* 1989: [[National Book Award for Nonfiction]] shortlist for ''[[Mother Country: Britain, the Welfare State, and Nuclear Pollution]]''\n* 1999: [[PEN/Diamonstein-Spielvogel Award for the Art of the Essay]] for ''The Death of Adam''\n* 2004: [[National Book Critics Circle Award#Fiction|National Book Critics Circle Award for Fiction]] for ''[[Gilead (novel)|Gilead]]''\n* 2005: Pulitzer Prize for Fiction for ''[[Gilead (novel)|Gilead]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulitzer.org/winners/marilynne-robinson|title=The 2005 Pulitzer Prize Winner in Fiction|website=www.pulitzer.org|language=en|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n* 2005: [[Ambassador Book Award]] for ''[[Gilead (novel)|Gilead]]''\n* 2006: [[University of Louisville]] [[Grawemeyer Award]] in Religion<ref name=grawemeyer.org>{{cite web|title=2006- Marilynne Robinson|url=http://grawemeyer.org/religion/previous-winners/2006-marilynne-robinson.html|publisher=Grawemeyer.org|accessdate=2015-10-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140404154918/http://grawemeyer.org/religion/previous-winners/2006-marilynne-robinson.html|archivedate=2014-04-04}}</ref> \n* 2008: National Book Award finalist for ''[[Home (Robinson novel)|Home]]''\n* 2008: [[Los Angeles Times Book Prize]] for fiction for ''[[Home (Robinson novel)|Home]]''\n* 2009: [[Orange Prize for Fiction]] for ''[[Home (Robinson novel)|Home]]''\n* 2011: [[The Man Booker International Prize|Man Booker International Prize]] nominee\n* 2012: Honorary Doctorate of Letters from [[Brown University]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Simmons among nine honorary degree recipients|url=https://news.brown.edu/pressreleases/2012/05/hdcitations#Robinson|publisher=Brown University|accessdate=28 May 2014|date=16 May 2012}}</ref>\n* 2012: [[National Humanities Medal]] for \"grace and intelligence in writing\"<ref>[http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/07/03/president-obama-award-2012-national-medal-arts-and-national-humanities-m President Obama to Award 2012 National Medal of Arts and National Humanities Medal] [[Whitehouse.gov]], retrieved 30 June 2013</ref>\n* 2013: [[The Man Booker International Prize|Man Booker International Prize]] nominee\n* 2013: [[Park Kyong-ni Prize]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20130926000648 |title=Park Kyung-ni literary prize goes to Robinson |work=Korea Herald |author=Julie Jackson |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2014}}</ref>\n* 2014: [[National Book Critics Circle Award]] for ''Lila''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/13/books/lila-by-marilynne-robinson-honored-as-top-fiction-by-national-book-critics-circle.html |title='Lila' Honored as Top Fiction by National Book Critics Circle |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |author=Alexandra Alter |date=March 12, 2015 |accessdate=March 12, 2015}}</ref>\n* 2014: National Book Award finalist for ''Lila''\n* 2015: Man Booker Prize longlist for ''Lila''\n* 2016: [[Library of Congress Prize for American Fiction]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/5a47ecfd55cf4f4ca70d3b1986471719/marilynne-robinson-wins-library-congress-fiction-prize |title=Marilynne Robinson wins Library of Congress fiction prize |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 29, 2016 |accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref> and [[Dayton Literary Peace Prize]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://daytonliterarypeaceprize.org/2016-holbrooke.htm|title=Dayton Literary Peace Prize - Marilynne Robinson, 2016 Recipient of the Richard C. Holbrooke Distinguished Achievement Award|first=Dayton Literary Peace Prize|last=Foundation|website=daytonliterarypeaceprize.org}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Marilynne Robinson}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Facebook}}\n* {{worldcat id|id=lccn-n80-90696}}\n* [http://worldvoices.pen.org/nonfiction-essay/recognitions Recognitions by: Marilynne Robinson] on her opinion of [[Marcel Proust]], PEN American Center\n\n{{Marilynne Robinson}}\n{{PulitzerPrize Fiction 2001\u20132025}}\n{{Mondello Prize}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Literature}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robinson, Marilynne}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Kent]]\n[[Category:American Congregationalists]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Pembroke College in Brown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Brown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Iowa Writers' Workshop faculty]]\n[[Category:Writers from Iowa City, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Pulitzer Prize for Fiction winners]]\n[[Category:University of Iowa faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Massachusetts Amherst faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Washington alumni]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Idaho]]\n[[Category:People from Sandpoint, Idaho]]\n[[Category:National Humanities Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:American women essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Hemingway Foundation/PEN Award winners]]\n[[Category:PEN/Diamonstein-Spielvogel Award winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century American essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American essayists]]\n[[Category:PEN/Faulkner Award for Fiction winners]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Iowa]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Marilynne Robinson\n| image = Mariliynne Robinson.jpg\n| caption = Robinson at the 2012 Festival of Faith and Writing at [[Calvin College]]\n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = Marilynne Summers\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1943|11|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Sandpoint, Idaho]], US\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| occupation = {{hlist | Novelist | essayist}}\n| alma_mater = {{unbulleted list | [[Pembroke College in Brown University|Pembroke College, Brown]] | [[University of Washington]]}}\n| residence = [[Iowa City, Iowa]], US\n| period = \n| genre = \n| subject = \n| movement = \n| notableworks = {{unbulleted list | ''[[Housekeeping (novel)|Housekeeping]]'' (1980) | ''[[Gilead (novel)|Gilead]]'' (2004) | ''[[Home (Robinson novel)|Home]]'' (2008) | ''[[Lila (Robinson novel)|Lila]]'' (2014)}}\n| spouse = {{marriage|Fred Miller Robinson|1967|1989|reason=div}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MKm8CgAAQBAJ&pg=PR11&lpg=PR11&dq=marilynne+robinson+husband+divorce#v=onepage&q=marilynne%20robinson%20husband%20divorce&f=true|title=This Life, This World: New Essays on Marilynne Robinson's Housekeeping, Gilead, and Home|date=2015-09-25|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9789004302235|language=en}}</ref>\n| partner = \n| children = 2\n| relatives = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = {{unbulleted list | {{nowrap|[[Hemingway Foundation/PEN Award]]}} (1981) | [[National Book Critics Circle Award#Fiction|National Book Critics Circle Award for Fiction]] (2004, 2014) | [[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction]] (2005) | [[Orange Prize for Fiction]] (2009) | {{nowrap|[[National Humanities Medal]] (2012)}} | [[Library of Congress Prize for American Fiction]] (2016)}}\n| signature = \n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Marilynne Summers Robinson''' (born November 26, 1943) is an American novelist and essayist. Across her writing career, Robinson has received numerous awards, including the [[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction]] in 2005, [[National Humanities Medal]] in 2012, and the 2016 [[Library of Congress Prize for American Fiction]]. In 2016, Robinson was named in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's list of 100 most influential people.<ref>[http://time.com/4298233/marilynne-robinson-2016-time-100/ 100 Most Influential People Marilynne Robinson] ''Time'', April 2016</ref> Robinson began teaching at the [[Iowa Writers' Workshop]] in 1991<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news-releases.uiowa.edu/1998/february/0204robinson.html |title=UI Writers' Workshop faculty member Marilynne Robinson win quarter-million-dollar award |date=February 4, 1998 |accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref> and retired in the spring of 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://now.uiowa.edu/2016/04/robinson-retire-iowa-writers-workshop|title=Robinson to retire from Iowa Writers' Workshop|date=2016-04-27|website=Iowa Now|access-date=2016-04-27}}</ref>\n\nRobinson is best known for her novels ''[[Housekeeping (novel)|Housekeeping]]'' (1980) and ''[[Gilead (novel)|Gilead]]'' (2004). Her novels are noted for their thematic depiction of both rural life and faith.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/apr/03/fiction.features2 | title=A love letter to lost America |date=April 2, 2005 |accessdate=March 29, 2016| newspaper=The Guardian | last1=McCrum | first1=Robert }}</ref> The subjects of her essays have spanned numerous topics, including the [[relationship between religion and science]], [[History of the United States|US history]], [[Sellafield|nuclear pollution]], [[John Calvin]], and contemporary American politics.\n\n==Life and career==\nRobinson was born on November 26, 1943 in [[Sandpoint, Idaho]], the daughter of Eileen (Harris) and John J. Summers, a lumber company employee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arts.gov/art-works/2010/marilynne-robinson-sandpoint-memories|title=Marilynne Robinson: Sandpoint Memories|date=2010-04-06|website=NEA|language=en|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=U59bAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT3279&dq=%22toJohn+J.Summers,+a+lumbercompany+employee,+and+Ellen+Harris+Summers%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwil59Kuz9jjAhWTHM0KHT9HAf0Q6AEwAHoECAAQAQ]</ref><ref>https://www.hillandwood.com/obituary/1887647</ref> Her brother is the art historian [[David Summers (art historian)|David Summers]], who dedicated his book ''Vision, Reflection, and Desire in Western Painting'' to her. She did her undergraduate work at [[Pembroke College (Brown University)|Pembroke College]], the former [[women's college]] at [[Brown University]], receiving her [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree ''[[magna cum laude]]'' in 1966, where she was elected to [[Phi Beta Kappa]]. At Brown, one of her teachers was the celebrated postmodern novelist [[John Hawkes (novelist)|John Hawkes]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MKm8CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA19&lpg=PA19&dq=marilynne+robinson+lewis+tappan#v=onepage&q=brown%20university&f=false|title=This Life, This World: New Essays on Marilynne Robinson's Housekeeping, Gilead, and Home|date=2015-09-25|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9789004302235|language=en}}</ref> She received her [[Doctor of Philosophy]] degree in English from the [[University of Washington]] in 1977.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.washington.edu/uwired/outreach/cspn/Website/Classroom%20Materials/Reading%20the%20Region/Northwest%20Schools%20of%20Literature/Commentary/9.html|date= n.d.|accessdate= 2008-04-13| title=  \t\n''History & Literature of the Pacific Northwest: Marilynne Robinson, 1943''|work= Center for the Study of the Pacific Northwest, [[University of Washington]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.litencyc.com/php/speople.php?rec=true&UID=5955 |title=Marilynne Robinson (1947\u2013 ) |accessdate=2009-06-22 |last=Lister |first=Rachel |date=2006-10-21 |publisher=[[The Literary Encyclopedia]] }}</ref>\n\nRobinson has written four highly acclaimed novels: ''[[Housekeeping (novel)|Housekeeping]]'' (1980), ''[[Gilead (novel)|Gilead]]'' (2004), ''[[Home (Robinson novel)|Home]]'' (2008), and ''[[Lila (Robinson novel)|Lila]]'' (2014). ''Housekeeping'' was a finalist for the 1982 [[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction]] (US), ''Gilead'' was awarded the 2005 Pulitzer, and ''Home'' received the 2009 [[Orange Prize for Fiction]] (UK). ''Home'' and ''Lila are'' companions to ''Gilead'' and focus on the Boughton and Ames families during the same time period.<ref name=PW>{{cite web|url= http://us.macmillan.com/home|title= ''Home'' by Marilynne Robinson|publisher= Us.macmillan.com|accessdate= 2015-10-29|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100722063909/http://us.macmillan.com/home|archive-date= 2010-07-22|url-status= dead}}</ref><ref>Dave Itzkoff, [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/04/books/04arts-MARILYNNEROB_BRF.html \"Marilynne Robinson Wins Orange Prize\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', June 3, 2009.</ref>\n\nRobinson is also the author of many non-fiction works, including ''[[Mother Country: Britain, the Welfare State, and Nuclear Pollution]]'' (1989), ''The Death of Adam: Essays on Modern Thought'' (1998), ''Absence of Mind: The Dispelling of Inwardness from the Modern Myth of the Self'' (2010), ''When I Was a Child I Read Books: Essays'' (2012), ''The Givenness of Things: Essays'' (2015), and ''What Are We Doing Here?'' (2018). She has written numerous articles, essays and reviews for ''[[Harper's Magazine|Harper's]]'', ''[[The Paris Review]],'' and ''[[The New York Review of Books]].''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://harpers.org/archive/2016/03/save-our-public-universities/|title=Save Our Public Universities|last=Robinson|first=Marilynne|date=2016-03-01|newspaper=Harper's Magazine|access-date=2017-02-05|issn=0017-789X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theparisreview.org/interviews/5863/marilynne-robinson-the-art-of-fiction-no-198-marilynne-robinson|title=Marilynne Robinson, The Art of Fiction No. 198|last=Fay|first=Interviewed by Sarah|newspaper=The Paris Review|access-date=2017-02-05|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nybooks.com/contributors/marilynne-robinson/|title=Marilynne Robinson|website=The New York Review of Books|access-date=2017-02-05}}</ref>\n\nShe has been writer-in-residence or visiting professor at many universities, including the [[University of Kent]], [[Amherst College|Amherst]] (where she taught, among other illustrious students, the novelist [[David Foster Wallace]]), and the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]]'s [[MFA Program for Poets & Writers|MFA Program for Poets and Writers]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/d-f-w-week-the-wonderfully-arrogant-first-pitch-letter|title=D.F.W. Week: The Wonderfully Arrogant First Pitch Letter|last=Max|first=D. T.|date=2012-09-07|access-date=2019-04-02|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref> In 2009, she held a Dwight H. Terry Lectureship at [[Yale University]], where she delivered a series of talks titled ''Absence of Mind: The Dispelling of Inwardness from the Modern Myth of the Self''. On April 19, 2010, she was elected a fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amacad.org/news/pressReleaseContent.aspx?i=113 |title=American Academy of Arts & Sciences |publisher=Amacad.org |date= |accessdate=2015-10-29}}</ref> In May 2011, Robinson delivered the [[University of Oxford]]'s annual Esmond Harmsworth Lecture in American Arts and Letters at the university's [[Rothermere American Institute]].\n\nIn the Spring of 2016, she retired as the F. Wendell Miller Professor of English and Creative Writing at the [[Iowa Writers' Workshop]]. Robinson still lives in [[Iowa City]], and spends the summers with family in upstate New York.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/jul/06/marilynne-robinson-interview-barack-obama-donald-trump-writer-theologian|title=Marilynne Robinson: \u2018Obama was very gentlemanly ... I'd like to get a look at Trump\u2019|last=Allardice|first=Lisa|date=2018-07-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-04-02|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> She was the keynote speaker for the Workshop's 75th anniversary celebration in June 2011. She gave the 2012 Annual Buechner Lecture at [[Frederick Buechner#The Buechner Institute at King University|The Buechner Institute]] at [[King University]]. In 2012, Brown University awarded Robinson the degree of Doctor of Literature ''honoris causa''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=MKm8CgAAQBAJ&pg=PR16&lpg=PR16&dq=awarded+marilynne+Robinson+the+degree+of+Doctor+of+Literature+honoris+causa&source=bl&ots=cu6rlSPU9J&sig=ACfU3U3eaqh3A5l1MVr6yQlARSvPn6cXVw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjxm7Grt7DhAhVVWysKHUe_AsAQ6AEwAnoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=awarded%20marilynne%20Robinson%20the%20degree%20of%20Doctor%20of%20Literature%20honoris%20causa&f=false|title=This Life, This World: New Essays on Marilynne Robinson\u2019s Housekeeping, Gilead, and Home|date=2015-09-25|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9789004302235|language=en}}</ref> On February 18, 2013, she was the speaker at the Easter Convocation of the University of the South, Sewanee, Tennessee and was awarded the degree of Doctor of Literature ''honoris causa''. The College of the Holy Cross, Notre Dame, Amherst College, Skidmore College, the University of Oxford, and Yale University have also awarded Robinson honorary degrees. She has been elected a fellow of [[Mansfield College, Oxford]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mansfield.ox.ac.uk/news/marilynne-robinson-awarded-honorary-fellowship|title=Marilynne Robinson awarded Honorary Fellowship {{!}} Mansfield College, Oxford|website=www.mansfield.ox.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-01-18}}</ref>\n\nRobinson was raised as a [[Presbyterian]] and later became a [[Congregational church|Congregationalist]], worshipping and sometimes preaching at the [[Congregational United Church of Christ (Iowa City, Iowa)|Congregational United Church of Christ]] in Iowa City.<ref name=\"Reform\">[http://www.reform-magazine.co.uk/index.php/2010/08/marilynne-robinson-interview-the-faith-behind-the-fiction/ \"Marilynne Robinson interview: The faith behind the fiction\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201235102/http://www.reform-magazine.co.uk/index.php/2010/08/marilynne-robinson-interview-the-faith-behind-the-fiction/ |date=2011-02-01 }}, ''[[Reform (magazine)|Reform]]'', September 2010.</ref><ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wnet/religionandethics/episodes/september-18-2009/marilynne-robinson/4244/ \"Marilynne Robinson\"], ''[[Religion & Ethics Newsweekly]]'', September 18, 2009.</ref> Her Congregationalism and her interest in the ideas of [[John Calvin]] have been important in many of her novels, including ''Gilead'', which centers on the life and theological concerns of a fictional Congregationalist minister.<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wnet/religionandethics/week829/interview.html \"Marilynne Robinson\"], ''[[Religion & Ethics Newsweekly]]'', March 18, 2005.</ref> In an interview with the ''[[Church Times]]'' in 2012, Robinson said: \"I think, if people actually read Calvin, rather than read [[Max Weber]], he would be rebranded. He is a very respectable thinker.\"<ref>Wroe, Martin, \"[http://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2012/22-june/features/a-minister-of-the-word A minister of the word]\", ''Church Times'', 22 June 2012</ref>\n\nThe former Archbishop of Canterbury, [[Rowan Williams]], has described Robinson as \"one of the world's most compelling English-speaking novelists\", adding that \"Robinson's is a voice we urgently need to attend to in both Church and society here [in the UK].\"<ref>Williams, Rowan, \"[http://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2012/10-august/reviews/book-reviews/mighty-plea-for-reasonableness Mighty plea for reasonableness]\", ''Church Times'', 12 August 2012</ref> On January 24, 2013, Robinson was announced to be among the finalists for the 2013 [[Man Booker International Prize]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.themanbookerprize.com/news/man-booker-international-prize-2013-finalists-announced |title=Man Booker International Prize 2013 Finalists Announced &#124; The Man Booker Prizes |publisher=Themanbookerprize.com |date=2013-01-24 |accessdate=2015-10-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924192855/http://themanbookerprize.com/news/man-booker-international-prize-2013-finalists-announced |archivedate=2015-09-24 }}</ref>\n\nOn June 26, 2015, President [[Barack Obama]] quoted Robinson in his eulogy for [[Clementa C. Pinckney]] of [[Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church]] in Charleston, South Carolina. In speaking about \"an open heart,\" Obama said: \"[w]hat a friend of mine, the writer Marilynne Robinson, calls 'that reservoir of goodness, beyond, and of another kind, that we are able to do each other in the ordinary cause of things.'\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2015/06/26/remarks-president-eulogy-honorable-reverend-clementa-pinckney |title=Remarks by the President in Eulogy for the Honorable Reverend Clementa Pinckney |publisher=whitehouse.gov |date=2015-06-26 |accessdate=2015-10-29}}</ref> In November 2015, ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'' published a two-part conversation between Obama and Robinson, covering topics in American history and the role of faith in society.<ref>{{cite journal\n| url = http://www.nybooks.com/articles/2015/11/05/president-obama-marilynne-robinson-conversation/| title = President Obama & Marilynne Robinson: A Conversation in Iowa| journal = The New York Review of Books| date = November 5, 2015| accessdate = August 21, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n| url = http://www2.nybooks.com/articles/s3/2015/nov/19/president-obama-marilynne-robinson-conversation-2.html| title = President Obama & Marilynne Robinson: A Conversation\u2014II| journal = The New York Review of Books| date = November 19, 2015| accessdate = August 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Personal life===\nIn 1967 she married Fred Miller Robinson,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sandiego.edu/cas/film/faculty-and-staff/biography.php?profile_id=74|title=Biography - Fred Miller Robinson, PhD - College of Arts and Sciences - University of San Diego|website=www.sandiego.edu|access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sheerhubris.com/tag/marilynne-robinson/|title=Marilynne Robinson|last=Sandra Hutchison|website=Sandra Hutchison|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref> a writer and professor at the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]]. The couple divorced in 1989.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theparisreview.org/interviews/5863/marilynne-robinson-the-art-of-fiction-no-198-marilynne-robinson|title=Marilynne Robinson, The Art of Fiction No. 198|last=Fay|first=Interviewed by Sarah|date=2008|work=The Paris Review|access-date=2019-01-03|issue=186|volume=Fall 2008|language=en|issn=0031-2037}}</ref> \n\nThe couple had two sons, James and Joseph. In the late 1970s, she wrote ''Housekeeping'' in the evenings while they slept. Robinson said they influenced her writing in many ways, since \"[Motherhood] changes your sense of life, your sense of yourself.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2009/may/30/marilynne-robinson|title=A life in writing: Marilynne Robinson|last=Brockes|first=Emma|date=2009-05-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-01-04|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Expand list|date=February 2015}}\n\n===Fiction===\n* ''[[Housekeeping (novel)|Housekeeping]]'' (1980) {{ISBN|9780374525187}}, {{OCLC|930404329}}\n* ''[[Gilead (novel)|Gilead]]'' (2004) {{ISBN|9780312424404}}, {{OCLC|1016128137}}\n* ''[[Home (Robinson novel)|Home]]'' (2008) {{ISBN|9780009732997}}, {{OCLC|588596243}}\n* ''[[Lila (Robinson novel)|Lila]]'' (2014) {{ISBN|9781844088812}}, {{OCLC|891809441}}<ref>[https://www.economist.com/blogs/theworldin2014/2013/11/cultural-forecasts \"Five books for 2014\"], ''The Economist'' November 21, 2013</ref>\n* ''Jack'' (2020)\n\n===Nonfiction===\n\n====Books====\n* ''[[Mother Country: Britain, the Welfare State, and Nuclear Pollution]]'' (1989) {{ISBN|9780374526597}}, {{OCLC|690002450}}\n* ''The Death of Adam: Essays on Modern Thought'' (1998) {{ISBN|9780312425326}}, {{OCLC|611655337}}\n* ''Absence of Mind: The Dispelling of Inwardness from the Modern Myth of the Self'' (2010) {{ISBN|9780300171471}}, {{OCLC|742007978}}\n* ''When I Was a Child I Read Books'' (2012)\n* ''The Givenness of Things: Essays'' (2015) {{ISBN|9781250097316}}, {{OCLC|930009863}}\n* ''What Are We Doing Here?: Essays'' (2018) {{ISBN|9780374282219}}, {{OCLC|988060584}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.92y.org/event/marilynne-robinson|title=Marilynne Robinson Introduced by Paul Elie|website=92 St Y}}</ref>\n\n====Essays and reporting====\n* {{cite journal |date=Winter 2011 |title=On \"beauty\" |journal=[[Tin House]] |volume=50}}\n* {{cite journal |date=November 2015 |title=Humanism, Science, and the Radical Expansion of the Possible |journal=[[The Nation]]|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/humanism-science-and-the-radical-expansion-of-the-possible/}}\n* {{cite journal |date=Fall 2015 |title=Fear |journal=[[New York Review of Books]] |volume=62 |number=14 |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/2015/09/24/marilynne-robinson-fear/}}\n* {{cite journal |date=Summer 2019 |title=Which Way to the City on a Hill?|journal=[[New York Review of Books]] |volume=66 |number=12 |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/2019/07/18/which-way-city-hill/}}\n\n====Interviews====\n* A September 2015 interview with [[Barack Obama]] in [[Des Moines]], [[Iowa]], recorded by the [[New York Review of Books]] and published in the October issues of the magazine in two-parts\n\n==Awards==\n* 1982: [[Hemingway Foundation/PEN Award]] for best first novel for ''[[Housekeeping (novel)|Housekeeping]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=PEN/Hemingway Award Winners|url=http://hemingwaysociety.org/?page_id=751|website=The Hemingway Society|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n* 1982: [[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction]] shortlist for ''[[Housekeeping (novel)|Housekeeping]]'' <ref>{{cite web|title=1982 Finalists|url=http://www.pulitzer.org/finalists/1982|website=The Pulitzer Prizes|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n* 1989: [[National Book Award for Nonfiction]] shortlist for ''[[Mother Country: Britain, the Welfare State, and Nuclear Pollution]]''\n* 1999: [[PEN/Diamonstein-Spielvogel Award for the Art of the Essay]] for ''The Death of Adam''\n* 2004: [[National Book Critics Circle Award#Fiction|National Book Critics Circle Award for Fiction]] for ''[[Gilead (novel)|Gilead]]''\n* 2005: Pulitzer Prize for Fiction for ''[[Gilead (novel)|Gilead]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulitzer.org/winners/marilynne-robinson|title=The 2005 Pulitzer Prize Winner in Fiction|website=www.pulitzer.org|language=en|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n* 2005: [[Ambassador Book Award]] for ''[[Gilead (novel)|Gilead]]''\n* 2006: [[University of Louisville]] [[Grawemeyer Award]] in Religion<ref name=grawemeyer.org>{{cite web|title=2006- Marilynne Robinson|url=http://grawemeyer.org/religion/previous-winners/2006-marilynne-robinson.html|publisher=Grawemeyer.org|accessdate=2015-10-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140404154918/http://grawemeyer.org/religion/previous-winners/2006-marilynne-robinson.html|archivedate=2014-04-04}}</ref> \n* 2008: National Book Award finalist for ''[[Home (Robinson novel)|Home]]''\n* 2008: [[Los Angeles Times Book Prize]] for fiction for ''[[Home (Robinson novel)|Home]]''\n* 2009: [[Orange Prize for Fiction]] for ''[[Home (Robinson novel)|Home]]''\n* 2011: [[The Man Booker International Prize|Man Booker International Prize]] nominee\n* 2012: Honorary Doctorate of Letters from [[Brown University]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Simmons among nine honorary degree recipients|url=https://news.brown.edu/pressreleases/2012/05/hdcitations#Robinson|publisher=Brown University|accessdate=28 May 2014|date=16 May 2012}}</ref>\n* 2012: [[National Humanities Medal]] for \"grace and intelligence in writing\"<ref>[http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/07/03/president-obama-award-2012-national-medal-arts-and-national-humanities-m President Obama to Award 2012 National Medal of Arts and National Humanities Medal] [[Whitehouse.gov]], retrieved 30 June 2013</ref>\n* 2013: [[The Man Booker International Prize|Man Booker International Prize]] nominee\n* 2013: [[Park Kyong-ni Prize]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20130926000648 |title=Park Kyung-ni literary prize goes to Robinson |work=Korea Herald |author=Julie Jackson |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate=July 7, 2014}}</ref>\n* 2014: [[National Book Critics Circle Award]] for ''Lila''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/13/books/lila-by-marilynne-robinson-honored-as-top-fiction-by-national-book-critics-circle.html |title='Lila' Honored as Top Fiction by National Book Critics Circle |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |author=Alexandra Alter |date=March 12, 2015 |accessdate=March 12, 2015}}</ref>\n* 2014: National Book Award finalist for ''Lila''\n* 2015: Man Booker Prize longlist for ''Lila''\n* 2016: [[Library of Congress Prize for American Fiction]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/5a47ecfd55cf4f4ca70d3b1986471719/marilynne-robinson-wins-library-congress-fiction-prize |title=Marilynne Robinson wins Library of Congress fiction prize |newspaper=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 29, 2016 |accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref> and [[Dayton Literary Peace Prize]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://daytonliterarypeaceprize.org/2016-holbrooke.htm|title=Dayton Literary Peace Prize - Marilynne Robinson, 2016 Recipient of the Richard C. Holbrooke Distinguished Achievement Award|first=Dayton Literary Peace Prize|last=Foundation|website=daytonliterarypeaceprize.org}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Marilynne Robinson}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Facebook}}\n* {{worldcat id|id=lccn-n80-90696}}\n* [http://worldvoices.pen.org/nonfiction-essay/recognitions Recognitions by: Marilynne Robinson] on her opinion of [[Marcel Proust]], PEN American Center\n\n{{Marilynne Robinson}}\n{{PulitzerPrize Fiction 2001\u20132025}}\n{{Mondello Prize}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Literature}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robinson, Marilynne}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Kent]]\n[[Category:American Congregationalists]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Pembroke College in Brown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Brown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Iowa Writers' Workshop faculty]]\n[[Category:Writers from Iowa City, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Pulitzer Prize for Fiction winners]]\n[[Category:University of Iowa faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Massachusetts Amherst faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Washington alumni]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Idaho]]\n[[Category:People from Sandpoint, Idaho]]\n[[Category:National Humanities Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:American women essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Hemingway Foundation/PEN Award winners]]\n[[Category:PEN/Diamonstein-Spielvogel Award winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century American essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American essayists]]\n[[Category:PEN/Faulkner Award for Fiction winners]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Iowa]]\n", "name_user": "Beth Timken", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marilynne_Robinson"}
{"title_page": "Alan West, Baron West of Spithead", "text_new": "{{short description|Retired Royal Navy admiral (born 1948)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix= [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name= The Lord West of Spithead\n|honorific-suffix= {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCB|DSC|PC}}\n|image=1SL Alan West (cropped).jpg\n|imagesize=\n|caption=West in September 2013\n|office= [[Minister for Security|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Security and Counter-Terrorism]]\n|primeminister= [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start= 28 June 2007\n|term_end= 11 May 2010\n|predecessor= [[Tony McNulty]]\n|successor= [[Pauline Neville-Jones, Baroness Neville-Jones|The Baroness Neville-Jones]]\n|office1 = [[First Sea Lord]]<br/>\n[[First Sea Lord|Chief of Naval Staff]]\n|primeminister1 = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start1 = September 2002\n|term_end1 = February 2006\n|predecessor1 = [[Nigel Essenhigh|Sir Nigel Essenhigh]]\n|successor1 = [[Jonathon Band|Sir Jonathon Band]]\n|office2 = [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor of]]  [[Solent University]] \n|term_start2= 28 June 2006\n|term_end2= 1 October 2018\n|deputy2= Professor Graham Baldwin\n|successor2= [[Theo Paphitis]]\n| office3           = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start3       = 9 July 2007<br/>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n| term_end3         =\n\n|party= [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|birth_date= {{Birth date and age|1948|04|21|df=y}}\n|birth_place= [[London]], United Kingdom\n|nickname=\n|spouse= {{marriage|Rosemary Anne Linington Childs|1973}}\n|children=\n|allegiance= United Kingdom\n|branch= [[Royal Navy]]\n|serviceyears= 1965\u20132006\n|rank= [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]]\n|unit= \n|commands= [[First Sea Lord]]<br/>[[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]]<br/>[[Defence Intelligence|Chief of Defence Intelligence]]<br/>[[Commander United Kingdom Maritime Forces|Commander United Kingdom Task Group]]<br/>[[Naval Staff Directorate|Director of Naval Staff Duties]]<br/>{{HMS|Bristol|D23|6}}<br/>{{HMS|Ardent|F184|6}}<br/>HMS ''Yarnton''\n|battles= [[Falklands War]]<br/>[[Iraq War]]\n|mawards= [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]]<br/>[[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Cross]]\n}}\n'''Alan William John West, Baron West of Spithead''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCB|DSC|PC}} (born 21&nbsp;April 1948) is a retired [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|admiral]] of the [[Royal Navy]] and formerly, from June 2007 to May 2010, a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] at the British [[Home Office]] with responsibility for security and a security advisor to Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]]. Prior to his ministerial appointment, he was [[First Sea Lord]] and Chief of the Naval Staff from 2002 to 2006.\n\n==Early career in the Royal Navy==\nWest was born on 21 April 1948 in [[Metropolitan Borough of Lambeth|Lambeth]], [[London]], and was educated at Windsor Grammar School (now known as [[The Windsor Boys' School]]) and [[Clydebank High School]].<ref name=WW>''[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who]] 2010'', [[A & C Black]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-408-11414-8}}</ref> He joined [[Britannia Royal Naval College]] in 1965 and served in [[HMS Albion (R07)|HMS ''Albion'']] during her standby duty for the [[Nigerian Civil War]] and circumnavigated the globe in [[HMS Whitby (F36)|HMS ''Whitby'']], taking part in the [[Beira Patrol]]. He was confirmed as a [[sub-lieutenant]] on 1 September 1969,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=44987 |supp=y|page=12549|date=12 December 1969}}</ref> and promoted to [[lieutenant]] on 1 May 1970.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=45092 |supp=y|page=5038|date=1 May 1970}}</ref> After his command of the [[Ton-class minesweeper]] HMS ''Yarnton'' in Hong Kong in 1973, he qualified as a principal warfare officer in 1975 and then served as operations officer in the frigate [[HMS Juno (F52)|HMS ''Juno'']] in 1976 and then the frigate [[HMS Ambuscade (F172)|HMS ''Ambuscade'']] in 1977.<ref name=WW/> Promoted to [[lieutenant commander]] on 1 April 1978,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=47527 |supp=y|page=5464|date=8 May 1978}}</ref> he attended the [[Royal Naval College, Greenwich|Royal Navy Staff College]] that year and then qualified as an advanced warfare officer before being posted to the [[destroyer]] [[HMS Norfolk (D21)|HMS ''Norfolk'']] in 1979.<ref name=WW/>\n\nIn 1980 he was promoted to [[commander]] and took command of the [[frigate]] [[HMS Ardent (F184)|HMS ''Ardent'']],<ref name=WW/> and deployed to the [[Indian Ocean]] taking part in the first [[Armilla patrol|Armilla Patrol]]. In 1982 he laid a wreath off [[Norway]], on the spot inside the [[Arctic Circle]] where the previous [[HMS Ardent (H41)|''Ardent'']] had been sunk in 1940 by the German battleships [[German battleship Scharnhorst|''Scharnhorst'']] and [[German battleship Gneisenau|''Gneisenau'']]. Shortly after, the ship deployed to the [[South Atlantic]] for the [[Falklands War]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=49194 |supp=y|page=16121|date=13 December 1982}}</ref> where she was sunk in [[Falkland Sound]] on 21&nbsp;May during the successful retaking of the islands.<ref name=culture24>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture24.org.uk/history+%26+heritage/war+%26+conflict/pre%2d20th+century+conflict/art32693 |title=First Sea Lord Admiral Sir Alan West On Nelson And Trafalgar 2005|publisher=Culture 24|date=21 December 2005|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref> West was the last to leave the sinking ship and was subsequently awarded the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Cross]] for his leadership.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=49134 |supp=y|page=12836|date=8 October 1982}}</ref> West led the victory parade through the City of London on return from the Falkland Islands. He remains the President of the HMS Ardent Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmsardent.org.uk/page5/page5.html|title=Admiral the Lord West of Spithead GCB DSC|publisher=HMS Ardent Association|accessdate=18 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024014839/http://www.hmsardent.org.uk/page5/page5.html|archive-date=24 October 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, while working on the Naval Staff at the Ministry of Defence, West left documents detailing large cuts to the Navy on a canal towpath. These documents were recovered and then published by a journalist from ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]''. At a subsequent court martial West pleaded guilty to charges of negligence and breaching security.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1391288/Officer-who-lost-plans-made-First-Sea-Lord.html |title=Officer who lost plans made First Sea Lord |publisher=The Telegraph |date=18 April 2002 |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref> He explained that they had fallen from his coat pocket whilst walking a friend's dog. West was issued with a severe reprimand, the second lightest sentence available. The reprimand was time expired before he became eligible for promotion to flag rank.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1569505/Profile-Admiral-Lord-Wests-change-of-tack.html |title=Admiral Lord West's change of tack |publisher=The Telegraph |date=16 November 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Senior Royal Navy career==\n[[Image:Warsash Deck 2011.jpg|thumb|left|The Former First Sea Lord in his capacity as Chancellor of [[Southampton Solent University]] with graduating [[British Merchant Navy]] officers in 2011]] Promoted to [[captain (Royal Navy)|captain]] in 1987, he was given command of [[HMS Bristol (D23)|HMS ''Bristol'']]<ref name=WW/> and the Dartmouth training squadron in March of that year and led the study into employment of women at sea before spending three years as head of naval intelligence<ref name=WW/> rewriting the NATO intelligence manual after the collapse of the [[Soviet Union]]. In 1992 he attended the [[Royal College of Defence Studies]],<ref name=WW/> where he produced a Seaford House Paper on why the UK needed a \u2018Grand Strategy\u2019. He attended the Higher Command and Staff Course at the [[Staff College, Camberley]] in 1993 before being promoted to [[Commodore (rank)|commodore]] and becoming [[Naval Staff Directorate|Director of Naval Staff Duties]] at the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] later that year.<ref name=WW/>\n\nWest became [[rear admiral]] on appointment as [[Naval Secretary]] in March 1994,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Senior%20Royal%20Navy%20Appointments%201900-.pdf |title=Senior Royal Navy Appointments |accessdate=18 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315105247/http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Senior%20Royal%20Navy%20Appointments%201900-.pdf |archivedate=15 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> responsible for officer appointing and also naval manning and  moved its organisation from London to Portsmouth. In February 1996 he became [[Commander United Kingdom Task Group]]<ref name=WW/> deploying to the Gulf for the first UK fighter patrols over Iraq (conducted by [[Sea Harrier FA2]]) and to the South China Sea to cover the withdrawal from Hong&nbsp;Kong (Operation OceanWave).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukdf.org.uk/assets/downloads/m17.htm|title=Naval deployment|publisher=UK Defence Forum|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1997 he was promoted to [[vice admiral]] and [[Defence Intelligence|Chief of Defence Intelligence]].<ref name=WW/> He was responsible for the move of the [[Joint Services School of Intelligence|Intelligence school]] from [[Ashford, Kent|Ashford]] to [[Chicksands]], and provision of intelligence to the Chiefs of Staff on operations in [[Sierra Leone]], [[East Timor]], [[Operation Desert Fox]] in [[Iraq]], and the [[Kosovo War]]. West was created a [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] in the [[2000 New Year Honours]].<ref name=kcb>{{London Gazette|issue=55710 |supp=y|page=2|date=31 December 1999}}</ref> He became a full [[admiral]] in November 2000 when he took up the post of [[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]], [[NATO]] Commander-in-Chief East Atlantic and NATO Commander [[Allied Joint Force Command Brunssum|Allied Naval Forces North]].<ref name=WW/> West co-ordinated the naval response to the [[September 11 attacks]] in the North [[Arabian Sea]] and [[Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/about-us/organisation/ministers/lord-alan-west/?version=1 |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20080727011901/http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/about-us/organisation/ministers/lord-alan-west/?version=1 |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 July 2008 |title=Lord West |publisher=Home Office |accessdate=18 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==First Sea Lord==\n[[File:Admiral Sir Alan West.jpg|thumb|Admiral Sir Alan West, then First Sea Lord, is pictured with the official chart of anchorages for the International Fleet Review]]\nWest was appointed as [[First Sea Lord]] and Chief of the Naval Staff in September 2002.<ref name=WW/> He was also a member of the [[Defence Council of the United Kingdom|Defence Council]] and [[Admiralty Board]] as well as [[First and Principal Naval Aide-de-Camp]] to [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]].<ref name=WW/> In his role he had overall responsibility for fighting effectiveness and morale of the Naval Service (Royal Navy, Royal Marines, Royal Fleet Auxiliary and medical services) for the successful operations on the US right flank in the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion of Iraq]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonspeakerbureau.com/uk/speakers/sir_alan_west|title=Sir Alan West|publisher=London Speaker Bureau|accessdate=11 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917060330/http://www.londonspeakerbureau.com/uk/speakers/sir_alan_west|archive-date=17 September 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring his time as First Sea Lord, West implemented the defence white paper entitled ''[[Delivering Security in a Changing World]]'' which proposed cutting three [[Type 23 frigate]]s, three [[Type 42 destroyer]]s, four nuclear submarines, six minehunters and reducing the planned purchase of [[Type 45 destroyer]]s from twelve to eight.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/lords/2004/jul/21/security-future-capabilities | title=Security: Future Capabilities HL Deb  vol 664 cc227-45 | date=21 July 2004 | publisher=UK Parliament}}</ref> In a message to the Royal Navy, West said \"We must continue the shift in emphasis away from measuring strength in terms of hull numbers and towards the delivery of military effects... I am confident that these changes will leave the Navy better organised and equipped to face the challenges of the future.\"<ref>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040812105400/http://www.royal-navy.mod.uk/rn/content.php3?page=1&article=816 | archivedate=12 August 2004 | url=http://www.royal-navy.mod.uk/rn/content.php3?page=1&article=816 | title=MESSAGE FROM THE CHIEF OF THE NAVAL STAFF | publisher=Royal Navy News Service | date=21 July 2004 | access-date=22 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he appeared on BBC Radio 4 and spoke about [[Trafalgar 200]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/factual/midweek_20051221.shtml |title=Sir Alan West|publisher=BBC Radio 4 \u2013 Midweek|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref> Trafalgar 200 was a celebration of the 200th anniversary of the [[Battle of Trafalgar]]. It saw an international fleet in the [[Solent]] led by Queen Elizabeth&nbsp;II and by the First Sea Lord. West led the demand by the Royal Navy for a major ceremony. He is credited with persuading the government to make the event include a large scale fleet review.<ref name=culture24/> In 2005 he served as the chief mourner at a reenactment of [[Horatio Nelson]]'s funeral.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov-news.org/gov/uk/news/first_sea_lord_chief_mourner_nelson39s_funeral/16746.html|title=First Sea Lord is chief mourner at Nelson's funeral re-enactment on Friday 16 September|publisher=Government News|accessdate=18 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110191731/http://www.gov-news.org/gov/uk/news/first_sea_lord_chief_mourner_nelson39s_funeral/16746.html|archive-date=10 November 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the [[2004 New Year Honours]], he was advanced to a [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]].<ref name=gcb>{{London Gazette|issue=57155 |supp=y|page=2|date=31 December 2003}}</ref> He completed his term as First Sea Lord on 6&nbsp;February 2006 and was succeeded by Admiral [[Jonathon Band|Sir Jonathon Band]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-12623656_ITM|title=Senior Royal Navy appointment|publisher=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Post-naval career==\nWest was installed as the first Chancellor for [[Solent University]] (formerly Southampton Institute and Southampton Solent) on 28 June 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portal.solent.ac.uk/news/channel/2018/march/students/we-are-solent.aspx|title=Solent University 2018|publisher=Solent University|year=2018|isbn=978-1-408-11414-8}}</ref><ref name=solent>{{cite web|url=http://www.solent.ac.uk/about-us/the-university/principal-officers/alan-west.aspx|title= Chancellor Lord West of Spithead|publisher=Southampton Solent University|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref> appointed to the board of the [[Imperial War Museum]] on 6 July 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehallpages.net/news/archive/94 |title=Sir Alan appointed to the Imperial War Museum |date=6 July 2006 |accessdate=18 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110191839/http://www.whitehallpages.net/news/archive/94 |archivedate=10 November 2013 }}</ref> and made chairman of the advisory board of defence contractor [[QinetiQ]] in October 2006.<ref>Private Eye No.1188, 6\u201319 July 2007, p.9, \"Tales of the Riverbank\"</ref> West will leave his role at Southampton Solent University in summer 2018 after the graduation ceremonies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.solent.ac.uk/news/life-at-solent/2018/were-bidding-a-fond-farewell-to-lord-west|title=We are bidding a fond farewell to Lord West|publisher=Southampton Solent University|date=10 May 2018|accessdate=1 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2010 West also became patron of the [[Docklands Sinfonia]] symphony orchestra.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.docklandssinfonia.co.uk/about |title=About us |publisher=Docklands Sinfonia |accessdate=18 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723153223/http://www.docklandssinfonia.co.uk/about |archivedate=23 July 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> In 2014 he presented the 15-part BBC Radio 4 series \"Britain at Sea\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b046czzn|title=Britain at Sea|publisher=BBC|accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref> He has been, since at least November 2014, a member of the [[Henry Jackson Society]]'s Political Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://henryjacksonsociety.org/people/council-members/ |title=Advisory Council \u2013 Political Council members |publisher=Henry Jackson Society |accessdate=4 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923022301/http://henryjacksonsociety.org/people/council-members/ |archivedate=23 September 2013 }}</ref> He is also a non-executive chairman of Spearfish Maritime Security.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spear-fish.com/ |title=Home |publisher=Spear-fish.com |date= |accessdate=2017-02-17}}</ref>\n\n==Political life==\nOn 29 June 2007, West was appointed Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State at the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Home Office]], with responsibility for security in the administration of Gordon Brown, and that same day Brown announced that West was to be created a [[life peer]]. On 9&nbsp;July 2007, he was created '''Baron West of Spithead''', of [[Seaview, Isle of Wight|Seaview]] in the County of [[Isle of Wight]],<ref name=barony>{{London Gazette|issue=58391|page=10139|date=13 July 2007}}</ref> and took his seat in the [[House of Lords]]. In November 2007 he told the [[BBC Radio 4]] ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' programme that he was not \"totally convinced\" of the need for 42-day detention (without trial) of terrorist suspects. But less than two hours later, following a meeting with the [[Prime Minister]], he said he was \"convinced\" of the need for the new legislation. The incident was an embarrassment for the government, particularly as West was the [[minister (government)|minister]] charged with navigating the controversial [[legislation]] through the House of Lords.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7097907.stm |title=Pienaar's view: Terror issue not plain sailing |publisher=BBC|date=16 November 2007|accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref> During his time with the Home Office, he produced the United Kingdom's first ever National Security Strategy (as trailed in his Seaford House paper of 1992) and Cyber Security strategy as well as formulating a series of other new strategies: the counter-terrorist policy, cyber security, chemical, biological radiological and nuclear security, science and technology for countering international [[terrorism]] and guidance for local government in enhancing the security of crowded places.<ref name=solent/> In May 2010, Lord West departed the [[Home Office]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-west-of-spithead/3834|title=UK Parliament - Biography|accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Post-Home Office===\nIn September 2011, he contributed to a book entitled ''[[What Next for Labour?|What Next for Labour? Ideas for a New Generation]]''; in his piece he highlights his view that [[defence spending]] under [[Tony Blair]] was insufficient.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.tomscholesfogg.co.uk/2011/10/admiral-lord-west-defence/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709210752/http://blog.tomscholesfogg.co.uk/2011/10/admiral-lord-west-defence/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 July 2012 |title=Admiral Lord West: Defence |publisher=Tom Scholes-Fogg |date=7 October 2011 |accessdate=18 August 2012 }}</ref> In August 2014, West was one of 200 public figures who were signatories to a letter to ''[[The Guardian]]'' opposing [[Scottish independence]] in the run-up to September's [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|referendum on that issue]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/07/celebrities-open-letter-scotland-independence-full-text|title=Celebrities' open letter to Scotland \u2013 full text and list of signatories|date=7 August 2014|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he challenged [[Michael Gove]] to a boxing match after Gove's reported comments ahead of the centenary commemorations that left-wing academics were spreading unpatriotic myths about the [[World War I|First World War]] via programmes like ''[[Blackadder]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/10926317/Lord-West-challenges-Michael-Gove-to-a-fight.html|title=Lord West challenges Michael Gove to a fight|work=Daily telegraph|date=25 June 2014|accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the June 2015 [[Sousse attack]], he said Britain must step up the \"propaganda war\" against the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL). \"They are running rings around us in terms of the social media they are putting out.\" He also suggested the West should consider working with Syrian president [[Bashar al-Assad]], whom he qualified as a \"loathsome man\", while he called for Britain to consider joining the US in conducting air strikes against ISIL targets in Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/tunisia/11701043/Tunisia-attack-shooting-gunman-tourists-victims-survivors-live.html |publisher=The Telegraph|title=Tunisia attack: chilling new video shows gunman firing shots as he is chased by hotel staff|date=29 June 2015|accessdate=1 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, following news emerging about serious power and propulsion problems with the Royal Navy [[Type 45 destroyer]], West argued it was a \"national disgrace\" that the Navy only had 19 destroyers and frigates.<ref name=guardian-20160129>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jan/29/royal-navy-warships-multimillion-pound-refits-power-cuts |title=British warships need multimillion-pound refit to stop power failures |author=Jessica Elgot |newspaper=The Guardian |date=29 January 2016 |accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref> In August 2016, he described the issues facing the MoD post-[[Brexit]] as a \"[[perfect storm]]\", insisting that there were great difficulties for the British military as a result of Britain's exit from the [[European Union]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-37034337|title=Ministry of Defence 'facing extra \u00a3700m costs post Brexit' |work=BBC|date=11 August 2016|accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, he expressed doubts as to whether Assad's government perpetrated the alleged [[Douma chemical attack]] and dismissed the [[White Helmets (Syrian Civil War)|White Helmets]] as having \"a history of doing propaganda for the opposition forces in Syria\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://talkradio.co.uk/news/former-naval-chief-syria-chemical-attack-could-be-propaganda-18041325517|title=Former Naval chief: Syria chemical attack 'could be propaganda' |work=talkRADIO|date=13 April 2018|accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1973, West married Rosemary Anne Linington Childs; they have two sons and one daughter.<ref name=WW/> West said that during one overseas posting in a foreign country, the [[Covert listening device|bugging]] of communications and accommodation was so widespread that Rosemary would say \"Goodnight everybody\" before turning off the light to sleep.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/world/us-warned-that-spying-on-allies-could-harm-fight-against-terror-8903362.html |title=US warned that spying on allies could harm fight against terror|last=Watts|first=Joseph|date=25 October 2013|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|page=8|access-date=13 February 2017|via=}}</ref>\n\nWest has admitted during security vetting to an extramarital affair,<ref name=\"Standard07\" /> and was forced to respond to rumours in 2007 about his friendship with [[Anni-Frid Lyngstad]] of ABBA with \"I'm not having an affair with her\".<ref name=\"Standard07\">{{cite news | url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/abba-star-and-i-are-just-friends-insists-browns-security-chief-6627069.html | title=Abba star and I are just friends insists Brown's security chief | date=16 December 2007 | newspaper=Evening Standard}}</ref> Newspaper reports at the time said \"He always had an eye for beautiful women\"<ref name=\"Standard07\" /> and that he was \"a bon viveur, fond of good wine, good food and good chat\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1572777/Admiral-West-denies-affair-with-Abba-singer.html | title=Admiral West denies affair with Abba singer | first1= Lewis | last1=Carter | first2= Richard | last2=Edwards | date=17 December 2007 | newspaper=Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n{{BLP sources section|date=April 2020}}\n<center>\n<br />\n[[File:Order of the Bath (ribbon).svg|100px]]\n[[File:UK Distinguished Service Cross BAR.svg|100px]]\n<br />\n[[File:South Atlantic Medal w rosette BAR.svg|100px]]\n[[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:Spange des K\u00f6nig-Abdulaziz-Ordens.png|100px]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:silver;\" align=\"center\"\n|Ribbon || Description || Notes\n|-\n|[[File:Order of the Bath (ribbon).svg|40px]] || [[Order of the Bath]] (GCB) || \n* Military Division\n* 2004 Knight Grand Cross  <ref name=gcb/>\n* 2000 Knight Commander  <ref name=kcb/>\n|-\n|[[File:UK Distinguished Service Cross BAR.svg|40px]] || [[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Cross]] (DSC) ||\n* 1982\n* <ref name=dsc>{{London Gazette|issue=49134|supp=y|page=12836|date=8 October 1982}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:South Atlantic Medal w rosette BAR.svg|40px]] || [[South Atlantic Medal]] ||\n* 1982\n* With [[Rosette (decoration)|Rosette]]\n|-\n|[[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|40px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]] ||\n* 2002\n* UK version of this medal\n|-\n|[[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|40px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]] ||\n* 2012\n* UK version of this medal\n|-\n|[[File:Spange des K\u00f6nig-Abdulaziz-Ordens.png|40px]] || [[Order of King Abdulaziz]]\n||\n* 2004 \n* 1st Class\n* Awarded by the [[Saudi Arabia|Kingdom of Saudi Arabia]] \n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n===Arms===\n{{Infobox COA wide\n| image             =\n| bannerimage       =\n| badgeimage        =\n| notes             = \n| year_adopted      = \n| coronet           = [[Coronet|That of a Baron]]\n| crest             = Issuant from Naval Coronet Or a demi Chinese Dragon Azure supporting with the foreclaws an Anchor Or\n| torse             = Or and Azure\n| helm              =\n| escutcheon        = Azure a Lymphad Or between the tops of four Towers issuant in saltire Argent\n| supporters        = On either side a Sea Lion Azure charged on the Chest with a Rose Or and resting upon a Naval Cannon the barrel to the centre also Or\n| compartment       =\n| motto             = '''Be Just And Kind'''\n| orders            = Order of the Bath\n| other_elements    = Pendant of the Distinguished Service Cross<ref>{{cite web|url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/5823027b29687f56941775d9/t/5a69fb6d0d92973b8c10ed51/1516895115465/IMG_4191.JPG?format=1000w|title=Photograph of the Coat of Arms|accessdate=6 April 2019}}</ref>\n| banner            =\n| badge             =\n| symbolism         = \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Alan West, Baron West of Spithead}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120528094342/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/alan-west/21800 Parliament Biography]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080503004926/http://www.hmsardent.org.uk/page5/page5.html Biography] HMS Ardent Association\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6251788.stm \"Brown brings in more 'outsiders'\"] BBC News, 29 June 2007\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Naval Secretary]]|before=[[Malcolm Rutherford]]|after=[[Fabian Malbon]]|years=1994\u20131996}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = [[John Paul Foley|Sir John Foley]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Defence Intelligence|Chief of Defence Intelligence]]| years = 1997\u20132000}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Joe French|Sir Joe French]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = [[Nigel Essenhigh|Sir Nigel Essenhigh]]|rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]]| years = 2000\u20132002}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Jonathon Band|Sir Jonathon Band]]|rows=2}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title = [[First Sea Lord]]| years = 2002\u20132006}}\n{{s-prec|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Baron Malloch-Brown|The Lord Malloch-Brown]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom|Gentlemen]]'''<br />''Baron West of Spithead'' '''}}\n{{s-fol|after=[[Baron Jones of Birmingham|The Lord Jones of Birmingham]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{First Sea Lord}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:West, Alan}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Graduates of Britannia Royal Naval College]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the Falklands War]]\n[[Category:First Sea Lords]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers|West of Spithead]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People associated with Solent University]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Abdulaziz al Saud]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Trafalgar 200]]\n[[Category:Qinetiq]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Retired Royal Navy admiral (born 1948)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix= [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name= The Lord West of Spithead\n|honorific-suffix= {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCB|DSC|PC}}\n|image=1SL Alan West (cropped).jpg\n|imagesize=\n|caption=West in September 2013\n|office= [[Minister for Security|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Security and Counter-Terrorism]]\n|primeminister= [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start= 28 June 2007\n|term_end= 11 May 2010\n|predecessor= [[Tony McNulty]]\n|successor= [[Pauline Neville-Jones, Baroness Neville-Jones|The Baroness Neville-Jones]]\n|office1 = [[First Sea Lord]]<br/>\n[[First Sea Lord|Chief of Naval Staff]]\n|primeminister1 = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start1 = September 2002\n|term_end1 = February 2006\n|predecessor1 = [[Nigel Essenhigh|Sir Nigel Essenhigh]]\n|successor1 = [[Jonathon Band|Sir Jonathon Band]]\n|office2 = [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor of]]  [[Solent University]] \n|term_start2= 28 June 2006\n|term_end2= 1 October 2018\n|deputy2= Professor Graham Baldwin\n|successor2= [[Theo Paphitis]]\n| office3           = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start3       = 9 July 2007<br/>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n| term_end3         =\n\n|party= [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|birth_date= {{Birth date and age|1948|04|21|df=y}}\n|birth_place= [[London]], United Kingdom\n|nickname=\n|spouse= {{marriage|Rosemary Anne Linington Childs|1973}}\n|children=\n|allegiance= United Kingdom\n|branch= [[Royal Navy]]\n|serviceyears= 1965\u20132006\n|rank= [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]]\n|unit= \n|commands= [[First Sea Lord]]<br/>[[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]]<br/>[[Defence Intelligence|Chief of Defence Intelligence]]<br/>[[Commander United Kingdom Maritime Forces|Commander United Kingdom Task Group]]<br/>[[Naval Staff Directorate|Director of Naval Staff Duties]]<br/>{{HMS|Bristol|D23|6}}<br/>{{HMS|Ardent|F184|6}}<br/>HMS ''Yarnton''\n|battles= [[Falklands War]]<br/>[[Iraq War]]\n|mawards= [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]]<br/>[[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Cross]]\n}}\n'''Alan William John West, Baron West of Spithead''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCB|DSC|PC}} (born 21&nbsp;April 1948) is a retired [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|admiral]] of the [[Royal Navy]] and formerly, from June 2007 to May 2010, a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] at the British [[Home Office]] with responsibility for security and a security advisor to Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]]. Prior to his ministerial appointment, he was [[First Sea Lord]] and Chief of the Naval Staff from 2002 to 2006.\n\n==Early career in the Royal Navy==\nWest was born on 21 April 1948 in [[Metropolitan Borough of Lambeth|Lambeth]], [[London]], and was educated at Windsor Grammar School (now known as [[The Windsor Boys' School]]) and [[Clydebank High School]].<ref name=WW>''[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who]] 2010'', [[A & C Black]], 2010, {{ISBN|978-1-408-11414-8}}</ref> He joined [[Britannia Royal Naval College]] in 1965 and served in [[HMS Albion (R07)|HMS ''Albion'']] during her standby duty for the [[Nigerian Civil War]] and circumnavigated the globe in [[HMS Whitby (F36)|HMS ''Whitby'']], taking part in the [[Beira Patrol]]. He was confirmed as a [[sub-lieutenant]] on 1 September 1969,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=44987 |supp=y|page=12549|date=12 December 1969}}</ref> and promoted to [[lieutenant]] on 1 May 1970.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=45092 |supp=y|page=5038|date=1 May 1970}}</ref> After his command of the [[Ton-class minesweeper]] HMS ''Yarnton'' in Hong Kong in 1973, he qualified as a principal warfare officer in 1975 and then served as operations officer in the frigate [[HMS Juno (F52)|HMS ''Juno'']] in 1976 and then the frigate [[HMS Ambuscade (F172)|HMS ''Ambuscade'']] in 1977.<ref name=WW/> Promoted to [[lieutenant commander]] on 1 April 1978,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=47527 |supp=y|page=5464|date=8 May 1978}}</ref> he attended the [[Royal Naval College, Greenwich|Royal Navy Staff College]] that year and then qualified as an advanced warfare officer before being posted to the [[destroyer]] [[HMS Norfolk (D21)|HMS ''Norfolk'']] in 1979.<ref name=WW/>\n\nIn 1980 he was promoted to [[commander]] and took command of the [[frigate]] [[HMS Ardent (F184)|HMS ''Ardent'']],<ref name=WW/> and deployed to the [[Indian Ocean]] taking part in the first [[Armilla patrol|Armilla Patrol]]. In 1982 he laid a wreath off [[Norway]], on the spot inside the [[Arctic Circle]] where the previous [[HMS Ardent (H41)|''Ardent'']] had been sunk in 1940 by the German battleships [[German battleship Scharnhorst|''Scharnhorst'']] and [[German battleship Gneisenau|''Gneisenau'']]. Shortly after, the ship deployed to the [[South Atlantic]] for the [[Falklands War]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=49194 |supp=y|page=16121|date=13 December 1982}}</ref> where she was sunk in [[Falkland Sound]] on 21&nbsp;May during the successful retaking of the islands.<ref name=culture24>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture24.org.uk/history+%26+heritage/war+%26+conflict/pre%2d20th+century+conflict/art32693 |title=First Sea Lord Admiral Sir Alan West On Nelson And Trafalgar 2005|publisher=Culture 24|date=21 December 2005|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref> West was the last to leave the sinking ship and was subsequently awarded the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Cross]] for his leadership.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=49134 |supp=y|page=12836|date=8 October 1982}}</ref> West led the victory parade through the City of London on return from the Falkland Islands. He remains the President of the HMS Ardent Association.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmsardent.org.uk/page5/page5.html|title=Admiral the Lord West of Spithead GCB DSC|publisher=HMS Ardent Association|accessdate=18 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024014839/http://www.hmsardent.org.uk/page5/page5.html|archive-date=24 October 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, while working on the Naval Staff at the Ministry of Defence, West left documents detailing large cuts to the Navy on a canal towpath. These documents were recovered and then published by a journalist from ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]''. At a subsequent court martial West pleaded guilty to charges of negligence and breaching security.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1391288/Officer-who-lost-plans-made-First-Sea-Lord.html |title=Officer who lost plans made First Sea Lord |publisher=The Telegraph |date=18 April 2002 |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref> He explained that they had fallen from his coat pocket whilst walking a friend's dog. West was issued with a severe reprimand, the second lightest sentence available. The reprimand was time expired before he became eligible for promotion to flag rank.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1569505/Profile-Admiral-Lord-Wests-change-of-tack.html |title=Admiral Lord West's change of tack |publisher=The Telegraph |date=16 November 2007 |accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Senior Royal Navy career==\n[[Image:Warsash Deck 2011.jpg|thumb|left|The Former First Sea Lord in his capacity as Chancellor of [[Southampton Solent University]] with graduating [[British Merchant Navy]] officers in 2011]] Promoted to [[captain (Royal Navy)|captain]] in 1987, he was given command of [[HMS Bristol (D23)|HMS ''Bristol'']]<ref name=WW/> and the Dartmouth training squadron in March of that year and led the study into employment of women at sea before spending three years as head of naval intelligence<ref name=WW/> rewriting the NATO intelligence manual after the collapse of the [[Soviet Union]]. In 1992 he attended the [[Royal College of Defence Studies]],<ref name=WW/> where he produced a Seaford House Paper on why the UK needed a \u2018Grand Strategy\u2019. He attended the Higher Command and Staff Course at the [[Staff College, Camberley]] in 1993 before being promoted to [[Commodore (rank)|commodore]] and becoming [[Naval Staff Directorate|Director of Naval Staff Duties]] at the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] later that year.<ref name=WW/>\n\nWest became [[rear admiral]] on appointment as [[Naval Secretary]] in March 1994,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Senior%20Royal%20Navy%20Appointments%201900-.pdf |title=Senior Royal Navy Appointments |accessdate=18 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315105247/http://www.gulabin.com/armynavy/pdf/Senior%20Royal%20Navy%20Appointments%201900-.pdf |archivedate=15 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> responsible for officer appointing and also naval manning and  moved its organisation from London to Portsmouth. In February 1996 he became [[Commander United Kingdom Task Group]]<ref name=WW/> deploying to the Gulf for the first UK fighter patrols over Iraq (conducted by [[Sea Harrier FA2]]) and to the South China Sea to cover the withdrawal from Hong&nbsp;Kong (Operation OceanWave).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukdf.org.uk/assets/downloads/m17.htm|title=Naval deployment|publisher=UK Defence Forum|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1997 he was promoted to [[vice admiral]] and [[Defence Intelligence|Chief of Defence Intelligence]].<ref name=WW/> He was responsible for the move of the [[Joint Services School of Intelligence|Intelligence school]] from [[Ashford, Kent|Ashford]] to [[Chicksands]], and provision of intelligence to the Chiefs of Staff on operations in [[Sierra Leone]], [[East Timor]], [[Operation Desert Fox]] in [[Iraq]], and the [[Kosovo War]]. West was created a [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] in the [[2000 New Year Honours]].<ref name=kcb>{{London Gazette|issue=55710 |supp=y|page=2|date=31 December 1999}}</ref> He became a full [[admiral]] in November 2000 when he took up the post of [[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]], [[NATO]] Commander-in-Chief East Atlantic and NATO Commander [[Allied Joint Force Command Brunssum|Allied Naval Forces North]].<ref name=WW/> West co-ordinated the naval response to the [[September 11 attacks]] in the North [[Arabian Sea]] and [[Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/about-us/organisation/ministers/lord-alan-west/?version=1 |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20080727011901/http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/about-us/organisation/ministers/lord-alan-west/?version=1 |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 July 2008 |title=Lord West |publisher=Home Office |accessdate=18 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==First Sea Lord==\n[[File:Admiral Sir Alan West.jpg|thumb|Admiral Sir Alan West, then First Sea Lord, is pictured with the official chart of anchorages for the International Fleet Review]]\nWest was appointed as [[First Sea Lord]] and Chief of the Naval Staff in September 2002.<ref name=WW/> He was also a member of the [[Defence Council of the United Kingdom|Defence Council]] and [[Admiralty Board]] as well as [[First and Principal Naval Aide-de-Camp]] to [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]].<ref name=WW/> In his role he had overall responsibility for fighting effectiveness and morale of the Naval Service (Royal Navy, Royal Marines, Royal Fleet Auxiliary and medical services) for the successful operations on the US right flank in the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion of Iraq]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonspeakerbureau.com/uk/speakers/sir_alan_west|title=Sir Alan West|publisher=London Speaker Bureau|accessdate=11 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917060330/http://www.londonspeakerbureau.com/uk/speakers/sir_alan_west|archive-date=17 September 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring his time as First Sea Lord, West implemented the defence white paper entitled ''[[Delivering Security in a Changing World]]'' which proposed cutting three [[Type 23 frigate]]s, three [[Type 42 destroyer]]s, four nuclear submarines, six minehunters and reducing the planned purchase of [[Type 45 destroyer]]s from twelve to eight.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/lords/2004/jul/21/security-future-capabilities | title=Security: Future Capabilities HL Deb  vol 664 cc227-45 | date=21 July 2004 | publisher=UK Parliament}}</ref> In a message to the Royal Navy, West said \"We must continue the shift in emphasis away from measuring strength in terms of hull numbers and towards the delivery of military effects... I am confident that these changes will leave the Navy better organised and equipped to face the challenges of the future.\"<ref>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040812105400/http://www.royal-navy.mod.uk/rn/content.php3?page=1&article=816 | archivedate=12 August 2004 | url=http://www.royal-navy.mod.uk/rn/content.php3?page=1&article=816 | title=MESSAGE FROM THE CHIEF OF THE NAVAL STAFF | publisher=Royal Navy News Service | date=21 July 2004 | access-date=22 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he appeared on BBC Radio 4 and spoke about [[Trafalgar 200]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/factual/midweek_20051221.shtml |title=Sir Alan West|publisher=BBC Radio 4 \u2013 Midweek|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref> Trafalgar 200 was a celebration of the 200th anniversary of the [[Battle of Trafalgar]]. It saw an international fleet in the [[Solent]] led by Queen Elizabeth&nbsp;II and by the First Sea Lord. West led the demand by the Royal Navy for a major ceremony. He is credited with persuading the government to make the event include a large scale fleet review.<ref name=culture24/> In 2005 he served as the chief mourner at a reenactment of [[Horatio Nelson]]'s funeral.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov-news.org/gov/uk/news/first_sea_lord_chief_mourner_nelson39s_funeral/16746.html|title=First Sea Lord is chief mourner at Nelson's funeral re-enactment on Friday 16 September|publisher=Government News|accessdate=18 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110191731/http://www.gov-news.org/gov/uk/news/first_sea_lord_chief_mourner_nelson39s_funeral/16746.html|archive-date=10 November 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the [[2004 New Year Honours]], he was advanced to a [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]].<ref name=gcb>{{London Gazette|issue=57155 |supp=y|page=2|date=31 December 2003}}</ref> He completed his term as First Sea Lord on 6&nbsp;February 2006 and was succeeded by Admiral [[Jonathon Band|Sir Jonathon Band]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-12623656_ITM|title=Senior Royal Navy appointment|publisher=Ministry of Defence|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Post-naval career==\nWest was installed as the first Chancellor for [[Solent University]] (formerly Southampton Institute and Southampton Solent) on 28 June 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portal.solent.ac.uk/news/channel/2018/march/students/we-are-solent.aspx|title=Solent University 2018|publisher=Solent University|year=2018|isbn=978-1-408-11414-8}}</ref><ref name=solent>{{cite web|url=http://www.solent.ac.uk/about-us/the-university/principal-officers/alan-west.aspx|title= Chancellor Lord West of Spithead|publisher=Southampton Solent University|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref> appointed to the board of the [[Imperial War Museum]] on 6 July 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehallpages.net/news/archive/94 |title=Sir Alan appointed to the Imperial War Museum |date=6 July 2006 |accessdate=18 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110191839/http://www.whitehallpages.net/news/archive/94 |archivedate=10 November 2013 }}</ref> and made chairman of the advisory board of defence contractor [[QinetiQ]] in October 2006.<ref>Private Eye No.1188, 6\u201319 July 2007, p.9, \"Tales of the Riverbank\"</ref> West will leave his role at Southampton Solent University in summer 2018 after the graduation ceremonies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.solent.ac.uk/news/life-at-solent/2018/were-bidding-a-fond-farewell-to-lord-west|title=We are bidding a fond farewell to Lord West|publisher=Southampton Solent University|date=10 May 2018|accessdate=1 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2010 West also became patron of the [[Docklands Sinfonia]] symphony orchestra.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.docklandssinfonia.co.uk/about |title=About us |publisher=Docklands Sinfonia |accessdate=18 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723153223/http://www.docklandssinfonia.co.uk/about |archivedate=23 July 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> In 2014 he presented the 15-part BBC Radio 4 series \"Britain at Sea\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b046czzn|title=Britain at Sea|publisher=BBC|accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref> He has been, since at least November 2014, a member of the [[Henry Jackson Society]]'s Political Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://henryjacksonsociety.org/people/council-members/ |title=Advisory Council \u2013 Political Council members |publisher=Henry Jackson Society |accessdate=4 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923022301/http://henryjacksonsociety.org/people/council-members/ |archivedate=23 September 2013 }}</ref> He is also a non-executive chairman of Spearfish Maritime Security.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spear-fish.com/ |title=Home |publisher=Spear-fish.com |date= |accessdate=2017-02-17}}</ref>\n\n==Political life==\nOn 29 June 2007, West was appointed Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State at the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Home Office]], with responsibility for security in the administration of Gordon Brown, and that same day Brown announced that West was to be created a [[life peer]]. On 9&nbsp;July 2007, he was created '''Baron West of Spithead''', of [[Seaview, Isle of Wight|Seaview]] in the County of [[Isle of Wight]],<ref name=barony>{{London Gazette|issue=58391|page=10139|date=13 July 2007}}</ref> and took his seat in the [[House of Lords]]. In November 2007 he told the [[BBC Radio 4]] ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' programme that he was not \"totally convinced\" of the need for 42-day detention (without trial) of terrorist suspects. But less than two hours later, following a meeting with the [[Prime Minister]], he said he was \"convinced\" of the need for the new legislation. The incident was an embarrassment for the government, particularly as West was the [[minister (government)|minister]] charged with navigating the controversial [[legislation]] through the House of Lords.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7097907.stm |title=Pienaar's view: Terror issue not plain sailing |publisher=BBC|date=16 November 2007|accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref> During his time with the Home Office, he produced the United Kingdom's first ever National Security Strategy (as trailed in his Seaford House paper of 1992) and Cyber Security strategy as well as formulating a series of other new strategies: the counter-terrorist policy, cyber security, chemical, biological radiological and nuclear security, science and technology for countering international [[terrorism]] and guidance for local government in enhancing the security of crowded places.<ref name=solent/> In May 2010, Lord West departed the [[Home Office]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-west-of-spithead/3834|title=UK Parliament - Biography|accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Post-Home Office===\nIn September 2011, he contributed to a book entitled ''[[What Next for Labour?|What Next for Labour? Ideas for a New Generation]]''; in his piece he highlights his view that [[defence spending]] under [[Tony Blair]] was insufficient.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.tomscholesfogg.co.uk/2011/10/admiral-lord-west-defence/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709210752/http://blog.tomscholesfogg.co.uk/2011/10/admiral-lord-west-defence/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 July 2012 |title=Admiral Lord West: Defence |publisher=Tom Scholes-Fogg |date=7 October 2011 |accessdate=18 August 2012 }}</ref> In August 2014, West was one of 200 public figures who were signatories to a letter to ''[[The Guardian]]'' opposing [[Scottish independence]] in the run-up to September's [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|referendum on that issue]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/07/celebrities-open-letter-scotland-independence-full-text|title=Celebrities' open letter to Scotland \u2013 full text and list of signatories|date=7 August 2014|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he challenged [[Michael Gove]] to a boxing match after Gove's reported comments ahead of the centenary commemorations that left-wing academics were spreading unpatriotic myths about the [[World War I|First World War]] via programmes like ''[[Blackadder]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/10926317/Lord-West-challenges-Michael-Gove-to-a-fight.html|title=Lord West challenges Michael Gove to a fight|work=Daily telegraph|date=25 June 2014|accessdate=5 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of the June 2015 [[Sousse attack]], he said Britain must step up the \"propaganda war\" against the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL). \"They are running rings around us in terms of the social media they are putting out.\" He also suggested the West should consider working with Syrian president [[Bashar al-Assad]], whom he qualified as a \"loathsome man\", while he called for Britain to consider joining the US in conducting air strikes against ISIL targets in Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/tunisia/11701043/Tunisia-attack-shooting-gunman-tourists-victims-survivors-live.html |publisher=The Telegraph|title=Tunisia attack: chilling new video shows gunman firing shots as he is chased by hotel staff|date=29 June 2015|accessdate=1 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, following news emerging about serious power and propulsion problems with the Royal Navy [[Type 45 destroyer]], West argued it was a \"national disgrace\" that the Navy only had 19 destroyers and frigates.<ref name=guardian-20160129>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jan/29/royal-navy-warships-multimillion-pound-refits-power-cuts |title=British warships need multimillion-pound refit to stop power failures |author=Jessica Elgot |newspaper=The Guardian |date=29 January 2016 |accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref> In August 2016, he described the issues facing the MoD post-[[Brexit]] as a \"[[perfect storm]]\", insisting that there were great difficulties for the British military as a result of Britain's exit from the [[European Union]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-37034337|title=Ministry of Defence 'facing extra \u00a3700m costs post Brexit' |work=BBC|date=11 August 2016|accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, he expressed doubts as to whether Assad's government perpetrated the alleged [[Douma chemical attack]] and dismissed the [[White Helmets (Syrian Civil War)|White Helmets]] as having \"a history of doing propaganda for the opposition forces in Syria\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://talkradio.co.uk/news/former-naval-chief-syria-chemical-attack-could-be-propaganda-18041325517|title=Former Naval chief: Syria chemical attack 'could be propaganda' |work=talkRADIO|date=13 April 2018|accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1973, West married Rosemary Anne Linington Childs; they have two sons and one daughter.<ref name=WW/> West said that during one overseas posting in a foreign country, the [[Covert listening device|bugging]] of communications and accommodation was so widespread that Rosemary would say \"Goodnight everybody\" before turning off the light to sleep.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/world/us-warned-that-spying-on-allies-could-harm-fight-against-terror-8903362.html |title=US warned that spying on allies could harm fight against terror|last=Watts|first=Joseph|date=25 October 2013|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|page=8|access-date=13 February 2017|via=}}</ref>\n\nWest has admitted during security vetting to an extramarital affair,<ref name=\"Standard07\" /> and was forced to respond to rumours in 2007 about his friendship with [[Anni-Frid Lyngstad]] of ABBA with \"I'm not having an affair with her\".<ref name=\"Standard07\">{{cite news | url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/abba-star-and-i-are-just-friends-insists-browns-security-chief-6627069.html | title=Abba star and I are just friends insists Brown's security chief | date=16 December 2007 | newspaper=Evening Standard}}</ref> Newspaper reports at the time said \"He always had an eye for beautiful women\"<ref name=\"Standard07\" /> and that he was \"a bon viveur, fond of good wine, good food and good chat\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1572777/Admiral-West-denies-affair-with-Abba-singer.html | title=Admiral West denies affair with Abba singer | first1= Lewis | last1=Carter | first2= Richard | last2=Edwards | date=17 December 2007 | newspaper=Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n\n<center>\n<br />\n[[File:Order of the Bath (ribbon).svg|100px]]\n[[File:UK Distinguished Service Cross BAR.svg|100px]]\n<br />\n[[File:South Atlantic Medal w rosette BAR.svg|100px]]\n[[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:Spange des K\u00f6nig-Abdulaziz-Ordens.png|100px]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:silver;\" align=\"center\"\n|Ribbon || Description || Notes\n|-\n|[[File:Order of the Bath (ribbon).svg|40px]] || [[Order of the Bath]] (GCB) || \n* Military Division\n* 2004 Knight Grand Cross  <ref name=gcb/>\n* 2000 Knight Commander  <ref name=kcb/>\n|-\n|[[File:UK Distinguished Service Cross BAR.svg|40px]] || [[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Cross]] (DSC) ||\n* 1982\n* <ref name=dsc>{{London Gazette|issue=49134|supp=y|page=12836|date=8 October 1982}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:South Atlantic Medal w rosette BAR.svg|40px]] || [[South Atlantic Medal]] ||\n* 1982\n* With [[Rosette (decoration)|Rosette]]\n|-\n|[[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|40px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]] ||\n* 2002\n* UK version of this medal\n|-\n|[[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|40px]] || [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]] ||\n* 2012\n* UK version of this medal\n|-\n|[[File:Spange des K\u00f6nig-Abdulaziz-Ordens.png|40px]] || [[Order of King Abdulaziz]]\n||\n* 2004 \n* 1st Class\n* Awarded by the [[Saudi Arabia|Kingdom of Saudi Arabia]] \n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n===Arms===\n{{Infobox COA wide\n| image             =\n| bannerimage       =\n| badgeimage        =\n| notes             = \n| year_adopted      = \n| coronet           = [[Coronet|That of a Baron]]\n| crest             = Issuant from Naval Coronet Or a demi Chinese Dragon Azure supporting with the foreclaws an Anchor Or\n| torse             = Or and Azure\n| helm              =\n| escutcheon        = Azure a Lymphad Or between the tops of four Towers issuant in saltire Argent\n| supporters        = On either side a Sea Lion Azure charged on the Chest with a Rose Or and resting upon a Naval Cannon the barrel to the centre also Or\n| compartment       =\n| motto             = '''Be Just And Kind'''\n| orders            = Order of the Bath\n| other_elements    = Pendant of the Distinguished Service Cross<ref>{{cite web|url=https://static1.squarespace.com/static/5823027b29687f56941775d9/t/5a69fb6d0d92973b8c10ed51/1516895115465/IMG_4191.JPG?format=1000w|title=Photograph of the Coat of Arms|accessdate=6 April 2019}}</ref>\n| banner            =\n| badge             =\n| symbolism         = \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Alan West, Baron West of Spithead}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120528094342/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/alan-west/21800 Parliament Biography]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080503004926/http://www.hmsardent.org.uk/page5/page5.html Biography] HMS Ardent Association\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6251788.stm \"Brown brings in more 'outsiders'\"] BBC News, 29 June 2007\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Naval Secretary]]|before=[[Malcolm Rutherford]]|after=[[Fabian Malbon]]|years=1994\u20131996}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = [[John Paul Foley|Sir John Foley]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Defence Intelligence|Chief of Defence Intelligence]]| years = 1997\u20132000}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Joe French|Sir Joe French]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = [[Nigel Essenhigh|Sir Nigel Essenhigh]]|rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]]| years = 2000\u20132002}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Jonathon Band|Sir Jonathon Band]]|rows=2}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title = [[First Sea Lord]]| years = 2002\u20132006}}\n{{s-prec|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Baron Malloch-Brown|The Lord Malloch-Brown]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom|Gentlemen]]'''<br />''Baron West of Spithead'' '''}}\n{{s-fol|after=[[Baron Jones of Birmingham|The Lord Jones of Birmingham]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{First Sea Lord}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:West, Alan}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lambeth]]\n[[Category:Graduates of Britannia Royal Naval College]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the Falklands War]]\n[[Category:First Sea Lords]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers|West of Spithead]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People associated with Solent University]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Abdulaziz al Saud]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Trafalgar 200]]\n[[Category:Qinetiq]]\n", "name_user": "Abraham, B.S.", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHonours and awards:tag BLP sources section", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_West,_Baron_West_of_Spithead"}
{"title_page": "Tiger (franchise)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox media franchise\n|title=''Tiger''\n|image= Tiger_film_series_logo.jpeg\n|caption= Franchise logo\n|creator=[[Aditya Chopra]]\n|origin=''[[Ek Tha Tiger]]''\n|books=\n|novels=\n|comics= ''Ek Tha Tiger: Saving The High Seas''<br />''Ek Tha Tiger: Caught In The Web''\n|magazines=\n|strips=\n|films=''[[Ek Tha Tiger]]''<br />''[[Tiger Zinda Hai]]''\n|tv= \n|plays=\n|musicals=\n|games= \n|rpgs=\n|vgs= ''Ek Tha Tiger'' (Android game)<br>''Ek Tha Tiger'' (Windows game)\n|radio= \n|soundtracks= ''[[Ek Tha Tiger#Soundtrack|Ek Tha Tiger]]''\n|music=\n|toys=\n|otherlabel1=\n|otherdata1= \n|otherlabel2=\n|otherdata2=\n|otherlabel3=\n|otherdata3=\n}} \n\n'''''Tiger''''' is an Indian [[media franchise]], consisting of two [[Bollywood]] films and a [[graphic novel]] series. The original work is 2012 film, named ''[[Ek Tha Tiger]]'', directed by [[Kabir Khan (director)|Kabir Khan]] and produced by [[Yash Raj Films]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ek Tha Tiger|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/cast/id/545809/Ek+Tha+Tiger|publisher=[[Bollywood Hungama]]|accessdate=6 March 2012}}</ref> \nIt centers on a fictional character, an Indian spy ([[Research and Analysis Wing|RAW]]) named \"Tiger\", who falls in love with a Pakistani spy ([[Inter-Services Intelligence|ISI]]).\nIt has a sequel named ''[[Tiger Zinda Hai]]'', directed by [[Ali Abbas Zafar]], that released on 22 December 2017.<ref name=\"DNA India\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-exclusive-it-s-official-katrina-kaif-opposite-salman-khan-in-tiger-zinda-hai-2254772 |title=Exclusive: It's official! Katrina Kaif opposite Salman Khan in 'Tiger Zinda Hai' |publisher=DNA India |accessdate=13 September 2016}}</ref> The sequel is based on the [[Foreign hostages in Iraq#India|2014 abduction of Indian nurses]] by [[ISIL]].<ref name=\"rediff\">{{cite news|url=https://m.rediff.com/news/report/iraq-isis-how-india-got-the-nurses-back-from-iraq/20140704.htm|title=The real story of Tiger Zinda Hai: How India got 46 nurses back from ISIS|work=[[Rediff.com]]|date=7 November 2017|accessdate=8 November 2017}}</ref> The first film also spawned a series of graphic novels, published by [[Yomics World]].\n\n==Films==\n===''Ek Tha Tiger'' (2012)===\n{{Main| Ek Tha Tiger}}\nAn agent code-named \"Tiger\" ([[Salman Khan]]){{spaced ndash}}India's top spy and an officer of the [[Research and Analysis Wing]] (RAW){{spaced ndash}}is conducting a mission in northern Iraq. Tiger is forced to kill one of his own men who has defected to [[Pakistan]]'s spy agency [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] (ISI). He subsequently kills many ISI agents in his escape from Iraq.\nTiger returns to [[India]] and reports to his boss, Shenoy ([[Girish Karnad]]), in [[New Delhi]]. He is immediately sent on a mission to [[Dublin]] to observe a scientist of Indian origin, Professor Anwar Jamaal Kidwai ([[Roshan Seth]]), who teaches at [[Trinity College, Dublin|Trinity College]] and is suspected of sharing his findings with the Pakistani defence establishment. Fellow RAW agent Gopi ([[Ranvir Shorey]]) accompanies Tiger on this mission. Tiger meets the scientist but fails to spend enough time for his observance and instead begins to spend time with the scientist's caretaker Zoya ([[Katrina Kaif]]), who is studying at a local dance academy. He tries to befriend Zoya to extract information, but begins to discover his human side as he grows closer to her. Tiger is attacked and robbed at his residence by a person suspected to be an ISI agent. Gopi repeatedly warns Tiger not to fall in love with Zoya, but his love cannot be stopped. Tiger asks Zoya for a date and there they both came to know about their feelings for each other. Before telling her his feelings, during a visit to dance academy, Tiger discovers that Zoya is an ISI agent and refuses to commit treason on Pakistan when he asks. Instead of killing Zoya, Tiger lets her go.\n\nSome time later, Tiger and Zoya meet again at a [[United Nations|UN]] Foreign Minister's Meeting in [[Istanbul]] when Zoya signals to him using a cryptic message. They decide to leave everything for their love and fool their respective agencies by taking a flight to [[Cuba]], having told their agencies that they are in [[Kazakhstan]]. Some years later, their agencies trace Zoya and Tiger due to a CCTV recording. They track them down in Havana, [[Cuba]], and the ISI agents catch Zoya. Tiger meets Gopi, who is searching for him for RAW, and having lied to Gopi that both Tiger and Zoya intend to return to India and cooperate with RAW, convinces Gopi to save Zoya from the ISI agents.  Instead of returning to India, the pair trick Gopi and escape aboarding an aeroplane. Tiger calls Shenoy, who tells him that RAW will find both spies. Tiger tells Shenoy that they will only return when Pakistan and India no longer need ISI and RAW. In the epilogue, several images of Tiger and Zoya in cities including [[Venice]], [[Cape Town]], [[Zurich]] and [[London]] are shown, where sightings of them have been reported. But neither agencies could catch them.\n\n===''Tiger Zinda Hai'' (2017)=== \n{{Main| Tiger Zinda Hai}}\nA sequel titled ''Tiger Zinda Hai'' was announced on 13 September 2016. Salman Khan and Katrina Kaif reprise their roles from the first film. In this film, Tiger is presumed to be dead by both the agencies, but it turns out that he is alive and fighting by himself against a global terror organization.<ref name=\"DNA India\"/> This sequel is based on the [[Foreign hostages in Iraq#India|2014 abduction of Indian nurses]] by [[ISIL]].<ref name=\"rediff\"/> Indian agent Tiger and Pakistani agent Zoya join forces in the name of humanity, against the militant messiah Abu Usman. Tiger Zinda Hai is an espionage action drama that follows a daring rescue mission in Iraq.\n\n===Unititled Third \"''Tiger''\" film (2021)===\nA third film and the last film of the franchise is currently under development and [[Ali Abbas Zafar]] will return as the director and will start scripting the film after the release his another film ''[[Bharat (film) | Bharat]]'' with [[Salman Khan]] which is an official adaption of the 2014 South Korean film ''[[Ode to My Father]]''.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Character\n! colspan=\"3\" | Film\n|-\n! style=\"width:20%;\"| ''[[Ek Tha Tiger]]'' <br>(2012)\n! style=\"width:20%;\"| ''[[Tiger Zinda Hai]]'' <br>(2017)\n! style=\"width:20%;\"| ''Unititled Third \"Tiger\" film'' <br>(2021)\n|-\n! Avinash Singh Rathore (Tiger)\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[Salman Khan]] \n|-\n! Zoya Humaini\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[Katrina Kaif]]\n|-\n! Shenoy\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Girish Karnad]]\n| \n|-\n! Captain Abrar\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[Gavie Chahal]]\n|-\n! Indian minister\n| colspan=\"1\" | Ashok Awasthi\n| colspan=\"1\" | [[Siddhartha Basu]]\n|\n|-\n! Gopi\n| [[Ranvir Shorey]]\n| colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|-\n! Professor Anwar Jamaal Kidwai\n| colspan=\"1\" | [[Roshan Seth]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|-\n! Abrar\u2019s assistant\n| colspan=\"1\" | Avinash Badal\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|-\n! Amelie\n| colspan=\"1\" | [[Lisa Byrne]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|-\n! Tokas\n| colspan=\"1\" | Ahran Chaudhary\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|-\n! Cuban guard\n| colspan=\"1\" | Jawed El Berni\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|-\n! Brad\n| colspan=\"1\" | Justin Fuentes\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|-\n! ISI agent Feroz\n| colspan=\"1\" | Troi Ge\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|-\n! Pakistani misister\n| colspan=\"1\" | Zarksis Khandhadia\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|-\n! Cuban boxer\n| colspan=\"1\" | Oscar Navin\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|-\n! News reporter\n| colspan=\"1\" | [[Juhi Parmar]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|-\n! Bagga\n| colspan=\"1\" | Rajender Sethi\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|-\n! Rabinder\n| colspan=\"1\" | [[Samar Jai Singh]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|-\n! Abu Usman\n| colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n| Sajjad Delfrooz\n| colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|-\n! Namit\n| colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n| [[Angad Bedi]]\n| colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|-\n! Firdouz aka Tohbaan\n| colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Paresh Rawal]]\n|-\n! Azaan\n| colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n| Paresh Paahuja\n| colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|-\n! Rakesh\n| colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Kumud Mishra]]\n|-\n! Hakim\n| colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n| Najmeddin Al Hadad\n| colspan=\"1\" style=\"background:#d3d3d3;\"|\n|-\n|}\n\n==Crew==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Occupation\n! colspan=\"3\" | Film\n|-\n!  \"width:10%;\"| ''[[Ek Tha Tiger]]'' <br>(2012)\n!  \"width:10%;\"| ''[[Tiger Zinda Hai]]'' <br>(2017)\n!  \"width:10%;\"| ''Unititled Third \"Tiger\" film'' <br>(2021)\n|-\n! Director\n| [[Kabir Khan (director)|Kabir Khan]]\n| [[Ali Abbas Zafar]]\n| [[Prabhu Deva]]\n|-\n! Producer(s)\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[Aditya Chopra]]\n|-\n! Screenplay\n| [[Kabir Khan (director)|Kabir Khan]]<br />[[Neelesh Misra]]\n| [[Ali Abbas Zafar]]<br />[[Neelesh Misra]]\n| [[Ali Abbas Zafar]]<br />[[Aditya Chopra]]\n|-\n! Story\n| [[Aditya Chopra]]\n| [[Neelesh Misra]] <br> Ali Abbas Zafar\n|\n|-\n! Composer(s)\n| [[Sohail Sen]]<br />[[Sajid-Wajid]]\n| [Vishal-Shekhar]]\n|\n|-\n! Background Score\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Julius Packiam]]\n|\n|-\n! Cinematography\n| [[Aseem Mishra]]\n| Marcin Laskawiec\n|\n|-\n! Editor\n| colspan=\"2\"